<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Deere-UAW 1stLd-Writethru a0775 10-09 0452</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deere-UAW, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0775,0463</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UAW Ratifies Deere Contract With Pay Raise, Job Security</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT to Karl sted Kark.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blue-collar workers at Deere & Co. plants in
five states overwhelmingly ratified a new contract with their first
general pay raise since 1981, United Auto Workers officials said
Sunday.
   The three-year pact won 90 percent approval in a vote Saturday
and Sunday at Deere facilities in Illinois, Iowa, Atlanta,
Minneapolis and Denver, the union's secretary-treasurer, Bill
Casstevens, said.
   The union does not reveal the actual vote on contract
ratifications, spokesman Karl Mantyla said.
   The agreement, approved by negotiators representing 13,500
factory workers, takes effect immediately.
   ``Obviously, we're very pleased to have a new three-year labor
agreement with the UAW,'' said Robert Combs, a spokesman for Deere.
   ``It addresses key areas of importance to both of us,'' he said,
citing operational efficiency, training, job security and
compensation.
   ``It's an agreement we can live with and work with,'' he said.
   The contract give Deere workers an average pay raise of 44.3
cents an hour in the first year, followed by lump-sum payments
equal to 3 percent of their base salary in each of the second and
third years of the pact.
   Union workers at Deere, the nation's leading manufacturer of
farm machinery, have earned an average $15.47 per hour.
   Deere's union workforce had not received a general pay raise
since 1981. The company has given only cost-of-living increases
using a formula tied to the consumer price index.
   The contract calls for a three-step increase in early retirement
benefits.
   The union also won important safeguards protecting workers from
layoffs. The contract guarantees jobs for all workers employed at
the time the pact was ratified.
   Deere is only able to lay off the remainder of its current
employees in times of high inventories, labor disputes, plant
closings, sale of a division of the company or an act of God.
   Company and union representatives negotiated daily for nearly
two months before a climactic 20-hour session that ended with
approval of the contract proposal.
   Deere and union officials had negotiated furiously to avoid a
repeat of the bitter five-month strike in 1986-87 that ended after
163 days with employees accepting a wage freeze and other
concessions.
   The union plans to soon resume contract negotiations with
Caterpillar Inc. The UAW has been meeting with negotiators for
Peoria-based Caterpillar for two months at a site in Bridgeton,
Mo., near St. Louis.
   Caterpillar, the world's leading manufacturer of earth-moving
equipment, and the union agreed to extend its contract, originally
set to expire Sept. 30, until the Deere talks were completed. The
Caterpillar contract affects 17,500 factory workers in five states.
</TEXT>
