<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GasPrices     10-09 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gas Prices,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Says Gas Prices Drop Nearly One Penny Over Past Two Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline prices nationwide dropped an average
of nearly one cent per gallon during the past two weeks, and more
price drops can be expected, an industry analyst said Sunday.
   Results of the latest twice-monthly survey of 12,000 gas
stations for the period from Sept. 23 to Oct. 7 shows an average
price for all grades, including taxes, of $1.0077 cents a gallon,
Trilby Lundberg, editor of the Lundberg Survey, said.
   The average was down about one penny from the previous survey,
Ms. Lundberg said.
   She said wholesale prices generally fell more than retail during
the same period, reductions that gas station owners may pass along
to consumers.
   At self-service stations, which have the majority of retail
sales, average prices were 91.31 cents for regular unleaded gas;
$1.06 for premium unleaded and 87.63 cents for regular leaded.
   Full service prices included: regular unleaded at $1.20; premium
unleaded $1.31; and regular leaded at $1.17, according to the
survey.
</TEXT>
