<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StonybrookDisturbance     10-09 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stonybrook Disturbance,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seven Arrested After Disturbance At School</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STONYBROOK, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of youths crashed a college
fraternity party Sunday, shot out windows and got into a fight that
left one student injured, Suffolk County police said.
   The police arrested seven Long Island youths and charged two of
them with the assault.
   All seven were charged with burglary and weapons possession
following the incident on the campus of the State University of New
York at Stonybrook, said Officer Linda Cicalese, a police
spokeswoman.
   The police were called to the school at 2:45 a.m. after
residents of a college dormitory reported hearing shots near a Phi
Beta Sigma fraternity fund-raiser, Cicalese said.
   The seven youths tried to gain entrance to the party and got
into a fight with Pedro Mojica, 20, of Brentwood. Mojica was cut on
the face with a knife or razor blade and was treated at Stonybrook
University Hospital, Cicalese said.
   Shots were fired through windows during the incident, but nobody
was wounded, said Officer Salvatore Yovino, another spokesman.
   Mojica knew the attackers, Cicalese said. She said she did not
know the cause of the fight, but said it was not racially motivated.
   Police stopped a car in Central Islip at 3:50 a.m. that matched
the description of a car fleeing the party, and recovered
.22-caliber semi-automatic rifle and a .32-caliber automatic
pistol, Yovino said, along with some stolen stereo equipment.
</TEXT>
