<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Lockheed-Health     10-09 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lockheed-Health,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Says Workers Not Endangered by Chemicals Believed Used on
Stealth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lockheed Corp. workers believed to be
assembling top-secret Stealth fighter planes have not been put at
risk by hazardous chemicals used in their work, a company official
said.
   ``I cannot emphasize too strongly that we have seen nothing to
indicate the materials we work with are fundamentally unsafe or
pose a health hazard, providing proper procedures are followed,''
John C. Brizendine, president of Lockheed's Aeronautical Systems
Co., said in an editorial in the company's employee newsletter
published Thursday.
   Seventy-five employees at the company's Burbank plant have filed
suit against Lockheed and firms making and supplying various
chemicals believed to used in making the fighter.
   About 150 employees have filed worker's compensation claims
charging they suffer from illnesses caused by dangerous chemicals.
   Lockheed workers claim composite materials used in the Stealth
fighter, designed not to reflect radar, and chemicals used to mill
or clean them are causing rashes, nausea, dizziness, memory loss
and lack of concentration, according to Rep. Howard Berman,
D-Calif., whose district includes Burbank.
   Inspectors from the federal Occupational Health and Safety
Administration and the Pentagon announced last week they were
inspecting Lockheed's facilities, but they have declined to comment
on what they have found.
   The employees have said security provisions forbidding them from
discussing their work with outsiders have hampered them from
seeking treatment from private physicians.
   However, Brizendine said employees could seek help from private
doctors and show doctors company lists of chemicals they use.
</TEXT>
