<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Paisley     10-09 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paisley,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say No Charges Expected In 1968 Death of Melvyn Paisley's
Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No charges will be filed in the 1968 death of the
second wife of former Boeing Co. executive and Pentagon probe
figure Melvyn Paisley, according to a report published Sunday.
   Paisley, the center of a Justice Department and FBI
investigation into bribery and bid rigging at the Pentagon, has
been married twice since Mary Lou Paisley's death.
   ``We have found nothing that would permit us to pursue criminal
charges against anybody,'' said Sgt. Harlan Bollinger, the homicide
detective who investigated the death of the Kent housewife for
three months.
   The investigation included an inquiry court session similar to a
grand jury proceeding. Police said they interviewed more than 50
people and examined all available evidence.
   The current King County medical examiner, Dr. Donald Reay, said
in June that the autopsy performed on Mrs. Paisley was inconclusive.
   Police said they can't say for certain how Mrs. Paisley died.
   The county prosecutor's office this week is expected to decline
to file formal charges from Mrs. Paisley's death, The Seattle Times
reported in its Sunday editions. She was 30 when she was found dead
in her young son's bathroom in the couple's home in the early hours
of May 8, 1968.
   At the time, Paisley told authorities that his wife, who was an
artist, apparently had gotten up during the night to paint and was
overcome by fumes while cleaning her brushes. He said she had gone
to bed earlier after having taken a drink and two sleeping pills.
   The autopsy found no trace of sleeping pills, alcohol or paint
solvent in Mrs. Paisley's blood.
   Paisley, a Boeing manager at the time of his second wife's
death, is a Washington, D.C., defense consultant.
   Paisley, who now lives in Virginia, said he had no comment.
   Nine months after Mrs. Paisley's death in 1968, Paisley married
his Boeing secretary. He divorced her in 1980 and married his
fourth wife, a 30-year-old Boeing computer analyst, Vicki McKim.
The fourth Mrs. Paisley has been implicated along with Paisley in
the current Pentagon probe.
   Reba Klimas criticized county police this summer for failing to
investigate the death of her sister, Mary Lou Paisley, 20 years
ago. Informed of the latest development in the case, she said, ``I
feel better about myself. I feel that we have at least tried to
find out what really happened to Mary Lou.''
</TEXT>
