<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Pakistan-Blast     10-09 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Pakistan-Blast,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twenty-two Hurt in Blast Aboard Bus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RAWALPINDI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb hidden in a bag of fruit and
bread exploded aboard an intercity bus, injuring 22 passengers,
three of them critically, authorities said Sunday.
   Police said the explosion occurred late Saturday night as the
bus was about to leave for the Punjabi city of Sialkot from
Rawalpindi's general bus stand.
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the attack,
but Pakistan has blamed scores of terrorist bombings over the past
two years on agents of Afghanistan's communist government.
   Pakistan arms and supports Moslem rebels who are fighting the
Kabul government and Soviet troops backing it up.
   Eyewitnesses said the saboteur hid the bomb in a bag of fruit
and bread which he placed at the front of the bus and then stepped
out, saying he was going for tea, according to police. The bomb
weighed about 6{ pounds, they said.
   The official news agency APP said three of the injured were in
critical condition. Police did not know how many people were aboard
the bus at the time of the explosion.
</TEXT>
