<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Mass-Anti-Nuclear     10-09 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mass-Anti-Nuclear,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Nuke Referendum Tops Massachusetts Ballot Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillion-dollar battle is being waged in
Massachusetts over a binding referendum that could produce the
nation's first voter-mandated shutdown of nuclear power plants.
   Voters here will decide on Nov. 8 whether to ban ``the continued
generation of electric power by commercial nuclear power plants in
the commonwealth by means which result in the production of nuclear
waste'' after July 4, 1989.
   Boston Edison Co., Yankee Atomic and other utilities have
funneled more than $5 million into an organization called Citizens
Against the Shutdown Initiative, outspending anti-nuclear activists
by nearly 20-1.
   Anti-nuclear activists collected 120,000 signatures to qualify
the referendum for the November ballot. Similar measures have
failed in Oregon, Maine and California.
   A poll by The Boston Globe in late September of 619 registered
voters said 49 percent opposed the referendum, 37 favored it and 14
percent were undecided.
   The measure, if adopted, would force the shutdown of Boston
Edison Co.'s troubled Pilgrim nuclear station in Plymouth _ a
16-year-old plant closed for the past 2{ years for nearly $400
million in safety, management and technical improvements after the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission rated it one of the nation's
worst-run nuclear plants.
   Boston Edison, confident it has corrected problems at Pilgrim,
has applied for NRC permission to restart the plant. Massachusetts
officials are still concerned about the adequacy of evacuation
plans.
   The state's other nuclear plant _ Yankee Atomic Electric Co.'s
station in Rowe in western Massachusetts _ also could be closed by
the referendum. Though relatively small and with a good operating
record, it is the oldest operating nuclear station in the country
at 28 years.
   ``We have two plants that have specific problems that really ...
increase the danger and the threat from radioactivity and potential
accidents,'' said Anna Gyorgy of the Citizens for Safe Energy
campaign promoting the referendum.
   Citizens Against the Shutdown acknowledges industry backing, but
claims both pro-nuclear and anti-nuclear members. The group says
the value of Pilgrim and Rowe should be studied individually with a
view to what alternative sources of power are available to replace
them.
   Gov. Michael Dukakis takes the same position and has opposed the
referendum for that reason.
   Opponents contend that if the referendum passes, the state will
be forced to compensate the utilities potentially up to $4 billion.
Supporters argue utility shareholders and ratepayers will pay.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
