<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Her ponytails have been close-cropped and
her figure isn't what it used to be, but Olga Korbut still has the
spunk and sparkle that won hearts and gold medals during the 1972
Olympics.
   The former Olympic gymnast toured sports facilities in
Indianapolis on Friday and visited officials of the United States
Gymnastics Federation.
   Korbut, 33, had been rushed through meetings and museums, but
still was filled with impish energy when she arrived at the Pan
American Plaza.
   ``My life is very interesting. It's almost as though someone is
watching over me and writing what my life will be,'' she said
through an interpreter.
   Korbut, who on Wednesday will be honored at the gymnastics
convention in California, retired from competition in 1978. She
continues to travel around the Soviet Union and recruit students
for the Byelorussia gymnastics school in Minsk.
   Two of her students made the Olympics in Seoul and Korbut
received a photograph of one of them from the U.S. Gymnastics
Federation.
   ``I will show this to her and say, `See, this is why you didn't
win,''' she said with a laugh.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Danny Glover says a student strike at
San Francisco State University 20 years ago helped make it possible
for him to star in such successful movies as ``The Color Purple.''
   ``My work as an actor has been affected by the strike here at
State,'' Glover told 600 people attending a rally Friday
commemorating the strike, which began Nov. 6, 1968.
   Glover, one of the leaders during the controversial six-month
strike, said the groups involved fought for racial equality and
ethnic studies, bringing the issues to the attention of a
previously indifferent nationwide public.
   The strike began after negotiations broke down between
administrators and the Black Students Union. It resulted in the
establishment of a School of Ethnic Studies in the spring of 1969.
   Admnistrators closed the school twice and more than 2,000
students were arrested and several faculty members were dismissed
after they joined strikers.
   Former Sen. S.I. Hayakawa, then president of the college, became
a national figure by taking a hard line against strikers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country music singer Buck Owens will
present the Country Music Foundation with a master set of taped
recordings of his 1966 concert at New York's Carnegie Hall.
   Owens, former co-host of the syndicated television show ``Hee
Haw,'' will make the presentation Wednesday, the foundation said.
   The foundation will use the recordings to produce and release an
album about the concert. The foundation operates the Country Music
Hall of Fame and Museum and reissues historic recordings.
   Owens' hit records include ``Act Naturally'' and ``I've Got a
Tiger by the Tail.'' He recently teamed up with Dwight Yoakam to
record the current hit ``Streets of Bakersfield.''
