<DATELINE>HIBBING, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The house where singer Bob Dylan carved
his initials on a wood plank in the basement when he was a child is
up for sale.
   A tiny classified ad in the current issue of Rolling Stone
magazine declares the availability of Dylan's boyhood home, 2425
Seventh Ave. E. in Hibbing. The property comes with original
furnishings, including a bunk bed.
   Real estate agent Curt Curtis said he placed the ad in Rolling
Stone because he felt the home could be of interest far beyond
Hibbing, perhaps as a museum or fan club headquarters.
   Curtis has gotten more than 100 responses to the ad and is
holding out for the $84,000 asking price.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ``Howdy Doody Show'' may have been canceled
28 years ago, but when nearly 1,000 fans turned up at a shopping
mall and Buffalo Bob Smith shouted out the familiar question, they
knew the answer.
   ``Hey, kids! What time is it?'' Smith hollered.
   ``Howdy Doody Time!,'' they responded in unison Saturday, as
fans had responded through the 2,543 times the program aired from
1947 to 1960.
   Smith, 70, was showing a little paunch in his fringed brown
buckskin suit with beige trim. The kids who once sat too close to
their 10-inch black-and-white televisions to watch him now have
beards and children of their own.
   ``I thought Howdy Doody was scary when I was growing up,''
37-year-old Kathie Diehl, who collects children's memorabilia from
the 50s and 60s and brought along her set of nine Howdy Doody
Little Golden Books in hopes of autographs.
   On stage, Buffalo Bob led the audience in singing the Howdy and
Clarabell songs, and played out with the speechless clown some of
the gags that worked so well on TV three decades ago _ like trying
to play music with a balloon as Clarabell sneaked up from behind to
stab it with scissors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHADRON, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA astronaut William Readdy says the
success of the recent flight of the space shuttle Discovery
provides hope and reopens the door to the future for the U.S. space
program.
   ``I asked the Discovery crew what I should tell you, and they
said to let you know that the dream is still alive. I think we
proved that to all the doubters and all countries with the launch
last week,'' Readdy said. ``The flight of Discovery has set us free
again.''
   Readdy addressed a group of about 200 people at Chadron State
College, where he was honored by the college faculty,
administration and students Friday. His appearance here was part of
the NASA Community Information Project, which has been touring the
Nebraska Panhandle.
   ``The last 32 months have been agonizing and painful, but the
successful launch of Discovery made it all worth while,'' said
Readdy, 36, one of about 60 active astronauts in the NASA program.
</TEXT>
