<HEAD>Former Haitian Dictator Looks Over Luxury Cars</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONACO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jean-Claude Duvalier of Haiti,
wearing jeans and a black leather jacket, paid a visit to a display
of 20 classic Ferrari automobiles being presented for auction.
   ``I don't want any photos. That could be misinterpreted,''
Duvalier said as he arrived Saturday. But he and two bodyguards
were unable to prevent photographers from taking his picture while
he looked over one of the cars.
   Duvalier ruled Haiti after the death of his father in 1971 until
he was ousted by nationwide protests in 1986 and fled with his
family to France. The Duvalier family amassed an immense fortune.
   The French government said Duvalier was to stay only a week, but
it has been unable to find another country to take him. He lives in
exile in a luxury villa in Mougins, 30 miles west of Monaco, but
rarely appears in public.
