<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-FreeDemocrats     10-09 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Free Democrats,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Figure In 1984 Scandal Elected To Head Political Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Prussian count and former
economics minister convicted last year of tax evasion was elected
head of The Free Democrats, junior partners in West Germany's
coalition government.
   Otto Graf Lambsdorff, who resigned as economics minister four
years ago during a scandal over alleged illegal political
contributions by the West German Flick industrial group, won the
job of party chairman Saturday.
   He defeated challenger Irmgard Adam-Schwaetzer for the job at
the Free Democrats' national party congress.
   In February 1987, a court convicted Lambsdorff of tax evasion
and fined him $96,000 but acquitted him on the more serious charge
of corruption in connection with the scandal.
   Lambsdorff denied any wrongdoing during his 18-month trial,
alleging the charges against him were politically motivated.
   The 61-year-old Lambsdorff takes over as the Free Democrats' new
chairman from Martin Bangemann, who is West Germany's current
economics minister.
   Bangemann is resigning as economics minister to take a seat next
year on the European Economic Community Commission in Brussels.
   Ms. Adam-Schwaetzer, 46, a high-ranking official in the West
German Foreign Ministry and a protege of Foreign Minister
Hans-Dietrich Genscher, received 187 votes to Lambsdorff's 211 in
Saturday's voting.
   The business-oriented Free Democrats are partners in West
Germany's coalition government, which also includes Chancellor
Helmut Kohl's Christian Democrats and the conservative Christian
Social Union.
</TEXT>
