<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 1119EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-IsBushATexan Bjt   10-09 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Is Bush A Texan, Bjt,830</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Does Bush, Born and Bred A Yankee, Qualify As A True Texan?
^By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEEVILLE, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every year, Vice President George Bush
totes a shotgun through the South Texas mesquite and huisache brush
to hunt quail and other birds, like many Texans.
   But does Bush, born and bred a Yankee, qualify as a true Texan?
   ``Texas is really his home and he loves the state. He comes down
as much as he possibly can,'' said Will Farish, whose Houston
company handles Bush's assets in a blind trust. Farish also owns
the 10,000-acre ranch where Bush has hunted for 20 years.
   Says Daniel Ouellette of Beeville, president of the Texas
Republican County Chairman's Association: ``He's lived in Texas
longer than I've been born.'' Quellette is 40.
   ``George Bush has been portrayed by some in the media as
Harvard, Northeasterner, wealthy, wealthy, wealthy,'' Ouellette
said. ``They don't do the same with Lloyd Bentsen. They look at him
differently.''
   Like Bush, the Democratic vice presidential candidate and native
of the Rio Grande Valley, often reminds Texas audiences that he's
``back home.''
   With Bush and Bentsen on opposing tickets and 29 electoral votes
in the balance, Texas has become a crucial battleground in the
presidential race.
   So how does each candidate claim the title of native son?
   Bush votes in Houston, reared his children in Texas, made a
respectable sum in the oil business and was elected to Congress
from Texas.
   He was born in Milton, Mass., in 1924, grew up in Greenwich,
Conn., and first came to Texas during World War II to train as a
Navy pilot at the Corpus Christi Naval Air Station.
   In 1948 he returned to the Lone Star State to take a job in
Odessa, in the middle of the West Texas oil patch. He was
transferred to California about a year later to sell drilling bits,
then returned in 1950 to Midland, near Odessa.
   He eventually formed Zapata Petroleum with partners that
included J. Hugh Liedtke, who later became head of the Pennzoil Co.
   ``George made a comfortable amount of money out of it,'' Liedtke
told The Associated Press in an interview earlier this year. ``It
was a substantial sum, but he's not what in Texas is called `Big
Rich'.''
   The Bushes and their five children later moved to Houston. Bush
became Harris County Republican chairman in 1962, ran
unsuccessfully for the U.S. Senate in 1964, won a House seat in
1966 and sold his 6 percent stake in Zapata for $1.1 million.
   Bush has not owned a home in Texas since he became vice
president in 1981.
   His legal voting residence is Suite 271 of the Houstonian Hotel
and Conference Center. His voting eligibility was challenged by a
Houston state representative because Bush purchased a home in
Kennebunkport, Maine, after becoming vice president, and has lived
in the vice president's residence in Washington, D.C.
   But Bush prevailed in the 1985 case, because the Texas
Constitution allows a voter to continue to claim state residency if
he is serving elsewhere in the federal government.
   He lost a 1984 battle with the Internal Revenue Service,
however, when he used the Maine address on his income tax return.
The idea was to avoid capital gains tax on profits from the sale of
his $792,000 Houston home by reinvesting them in the Kennebunkport
house.
   The IRS ruled that Bush's principal residence, the only one for
which the tax break was allowed, was Washington, D.C. _ not Maine _
and that he therefore had to pay.
   Attorney Harold DeMoss, who represented Bush at the June 3,
1985, hearing on his voting eligibility, presented Harris County
Assessor Carl Smith with documents proving that Bush owned
undeveloped land in Houston, had a Texas driver's license and
belonged to a Houston church.
   Bentsen lists the Arrowhead Ranch in Starr County as his voting
residence.
   ``I would guess on average he spends 35 percent of his time in
Texas and for the last two years I would say 50 percent,'' said
Jack DeVore, spokesman for Bentsen's race for re-election to the
U.S. Senate.
   Bentsen's father made a fortune in real estate and agriculture
in the Rio Grande Valley.
   Calvin Bentsen of McAllen, a cousin of the senator, said they
grew up together in South Texas working on their fathers' farms.
   ``He likes the valley,'' Calvin Bentsen said. ``He likes the
ranch life out there.''
   Bentsen's first elected office was as county judge of Hidalgo
County in 1947. He served in Congress from 1949 to 1954 before
dropping out of politics to become president of Lincoln
Consolidated, a financial holding company.
   Bentsen defeated Bush and was elected to the Senate in 1970.
   Some doubt whether voters will place much importance on either
candidate's Texas residency.
   Ouellette said people will judge Bush not by his residence but
by his conservatism.
   Besides, says ranch owner Farish, ``I don't know exactly what a
Texas accent is.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881009-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 1120EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Likability Bjt   10-09 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Likability, Bjt,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Image Experts: If You Like Your Dentist, You'll Love Dukakis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When political filmmaker Charles Guggenheim
was asked to list the qualities that Democrat Michael Dukakis
projects in this presidential campaign, he responded with this:
``controlled, efficient, knowledgeable, predictable, humorless.''
   What about likable?
   ``No, I don't think likable is one of them,'' he said.
   Is that a problem?
   ``Oh, it's a serious problem.''
   Guggenheim, whose career dates back to his service as Democratic
candidate Adlai Stevenson's television consultant in the 1950s,
expresses a widespread view that Dukakis has a serious image
problem which his TV campaign commercials are doing very little to
dispel.
   ``The smartest clerk in the world,'' was how ABC's Peter
Jennings, a panelist for the first presidential debate last month,
described the Massachusetts governor to preface a question about
his passionless, technocratic governing style.
   ``Passionless?'' responded the Democratic nominee with a smile.
``I care deeply about people, all people: working people, working
families, people all over this country.''
   But does that concern come across to people who watch Dukakis
debating or see him campaigning on TV news broadcasts?
   ``Dukakis comes across like your accountant or, God forbid, your
dentist,'' said New York media consultant David Garth. ``You know
you have to see him, but you don't look forward to it.''
   ``He is a very, very conservative guy and he is a very
deliberate guy and he has no natural sense of humor,'' said Garth,
who says Republican nominee George Bush doesn't display much more
appeal than Dukakis.
   ``I don't think there's any warmth or depth of feeling for
either one of these guys,'' Garth said.
   The public catches only rare glimpses of Dukakis in repose. He
takes a ``power walk'' every night, dressed in a casual warmup
suit, but photographers are not welcome. Bush, by contrast, jogs
regularly with reporters and cameras in tow.
   Judy Pearson, a professor of interpersonal communication at Ohio
University who has written extensively on how women react to
presidential candidates, said Dukakis' manner doesn't blend with
his message.
   ``He tends to be very stiff, cold,'' she said. ``He doesn't have
warmth, even though the message tends to be one of caring for
people, for the hungry and homeless.''
   She said his delivery of the words contradicts what he's saying.
   What she called his ``non-verbal message'' is ``cold, short
phrases being thrown out like bullets.''
   ``When people look at a verbal and a non-verbal message and
they're in contradiction, what we tend to do is subconsciously
believe the non-verbal message,'' she said.
   Kathleen Hall Jamieson, professor of communications at the
University of Texas and author of ``Packaging the Presidency,''
said Dukakis' gestures don't go over well.
   ``He originally had a pointing, thrusting gesture that looked
like he thought he was superior and giving a lecture, and the
problem with it was it underscored a tone that was subtle but real
in his speech,'' she said.
   ``He sounds as if he knows more than we do. The danger is you
can put a spin on that to suggest he's arrogant and patronizing and
moralistic and self-righteous.''
   ``We don't like people who think they're better than we are,''
she said.
   Is there something Dukakis could do to warm up his image?
   ``I'm not sure from my experience that a person like that is
changeable,'' said Guggenheim.
   ``I think they could make television films which would help
allay some of this problem,'' he said. ``But it would have to be
done by an outside hand. The moments in which he does show some
sensitivity, warmth and compassion are unguarded. ... They wouldn't
be dishonest moments. They just would be moments the candidate
doesn't feel are important.''
   Guggenheim and Garth independently offered almost identical
criticism of the series of Dukakis television ads in which actors
portray political advisers trying to create a positive image for
Bush.
   ``By putting those ads on themselves and being sponsors of them,
they (the Dukakis campaign) are showing they are no different than
the people they are criticizing,'' Guggenheim said.
   ``I think the ads are a disaster,'' Garth said.
   ``The message is, Bush is packaged, and we're delivering that
message in our own package,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
