<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 1135EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-MarketAftermath Bjt   10-09 0803</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Market Aftermath, Bjt,750</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 6:30 p.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Many Unresolved Complaints After Stock Market Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two out of three small investors who
experienced problems during the stock market crash are still
waiting a year later for their complaints to be resolved, according
to a survey released Sunday by state regulators.
   The North American Securities Administrators Administration said
64 percent of investors responding to a survey said their problems
arising from the collapse of the stock market in October 1987 had
not been resolved.
   ``This confirms our suspicions that small investors were and
remain the invisible victims of the Oct. 19 stock market crash,''
said John Baldwin, the new president of the NASAA, the national
organization for state securities regulators.
   ``A full year after Black Monday, those of us who regulate the
markets at the grass roots level are still finding a surprising
number of dazed investors stumbling through the ruins of their
post-crash finances,'' said Baldwin, who is director of the Utah
Securities Division.
   Baldwin said the organization's survey showed that investors who
had been burned were not rushing back into the market. One out of
seven small investors said they had bailed out of the market
altogether or were holding less than $500 in securities.
   Of those still in the market, two-thirds indicated they had
changed or were planning to change brokerage firms.
   The most common complaint, made by half of the survey
respondents, concerned problems with brokers executing trades late
or getting trades wrong during the hectic period surrounding the
crash. The next most common gripe, made by 33.7 percent of those in
the survey, concerned charges that their broker had misled them.
   Close behind at 30.3 percent were complaints concerning brokers
who put their customers in unsuitable investments such as a highly
risky venture for a customer without a lot of money to lose.
   Asked how long it had taken to resolve their complaints, an
overwhelming 64 percent of those responding said their complaints
were still not resolved. Some 3.6 percent said their problem had
been resolved in one month or less.
   Among the comments made in the survey:
   _ A housewife in Florham Park, N.J., who lost $50,000 invested
in stocks, wrote, ``My financial security has been drastically and
unnecessarily destroyed. Even if I were in a financial position to
invest now, I would never put my money anywhere but in the bank. I
could never have faith in brokers again.''
   _ A Pineville, Ala., engineer, who lost a $197,000 portfolio
accumulated in 20 years of investing, wrote, ``Since the stock
market crash I have been surviving day by day, depressed, trying to
forget about the stock market.''
   _ A retiree in Cape Gable, Fla., who complained that his broker
had never outlined the danger of option trading, said, ``I lost
basically everything we owned. We have now had to go back to work
to earn enough to live own.''
   _ A New York City public relations man wrote, ``This continues
to be one of the most painful situations I've ever experienced _ to
have lost so much money, which was hard-earned and difficult to
save, and to feel that I have nowhere to go for help and don't know
how to rectify the problem or recoup the loss.''
   Not all investors complained about their brokers. A Port Orange,
Fla., investor who complained to the manager of a major discount
brokerage house that his order placed on Oct. 20, 1987, had been
mishandled received a credit for more than $6,500, covering the
full amount of his loss.
   Baldwin said it was important for investors to know what avenues
of help existed for them to get their complaints resolved. He said
one of the best places to look for assistance was the investor's
state securities bureau.
   Baldwin said often state regulators were able to get results
just by getting the brokerage firm and the investor together to
discuss the problem.
   He said arbitration and court suits were also available,
although the survey found that both approaches were time consuming.
Of the cases that went to court, 90 percent of them were still
pending and 87 percent of the cases in arbitration were still
unresolved.
   The survey was based on responses to questionnaires mailed to
2,500 callers selected at random from 15,000 investors who have
used a hotline set up following the crash by the NASAA. A total of
829 investors returned the mailed surveys.
   The association said the typical respondent was a male, aged 55
or older, with a gross income of around $30,000, who had lost
between $1,000 and $5,000 in the stock market crash.
   The survey results were released at the start of the
association's annual convention in Sante Fe, N.M.
</TEXT>
