<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 1141EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Transportation     10-09 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Transportation,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bill Protecting Airline Passengers, Imposing Drug Testing Is
Snarled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill initially intended to improve airline
service is hitting a stone wall as Congress debates controversial
provisions that would protect jobs after industry mergers and
require employee drug testing.
   With the Senate and House hoping to adjourn for the year by
week's end, the chances seem bleak that negotiators from the two
chambers will work out a compromise and persuade President Reagan
to sign it.
   ``It's going to be very difficult to put it together,'' conceded
Sen. Wendell Ford, D-Ky., chairman of the Senate aviation
subcommittee and one of the legislators trying to shape the bill.
   The measure contains three separate initiatives that each are so
divisive that the legislation seems to be sinking under its own
weight.
   ``Certain members are on and off the reservation,'' said Rep.
Norman Mineta, D-Calif., chairman of the House aviation
subcommittee. ``It's like a chess game.''
   Each chamber passed its own version of the bill last October, at
the height of public fury over deteriorating air service and
concern about safety.
   The legislation would require the airlines to submit monthly
reports to the government on flight delays, lost luggage and other
problems. The Department of Transportation began releasing similar
figures last fall, but the bill would require a more extensive
reporting system.
   This section of the legislation is the basis for problem No. 1.
The House bill is much tougher on the airline industry, containing
one provision, for example, that would force carriers to provide
free tickets to passengers whose bags are lost. Ford says he wants
nothing tougher than the requirements the Transportation Department
has already imposed.
   Both chambers' measures also contain labor-sought language,
opposed by the airline industry, that would protect the jobs of
employees whose jobs are endangered by air carrier mergers.
   These provisions have strong support from most lawmakers, but
paradoxically they are ``the real hang-up'' in the bill, according
to Sen. Ernest Hollings, D-S.C., chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee.
   That is because the labor-protection provisions are so strongly
opposed by Reagan that administration officials say it would cause
him to veto the entire measure. The president's opposition seems so
steadfast that Hollings are some other lawmakers would prefer to
remove the language from the bill.
   ``I just don't believe in spinning my wheels just to make TV for
someone,'' he said. ``We've got work to do.''
   Problem No. 3 is over language in the Senate bill _ but omitted
from the House version _ that would set up extensive testing for
drug and alcohol abuse by employees in the airline, railroad and
trucking industries.
   Hollings and Sen. John Danforth of Missouri, the ranking
Republican on the Senate panel, have fought for the testing
provisions all year.
   The initiative was inspired by the Jan. 4, 1987, collision of a
Conrail locomotive with an Amtrak passenger train in Chase, Md., in
which 16 people died and 175 others were hurt.
   Two crewmen on the Conrail engine admitted later that they had
smoked marijuana shortly before the crash.
   But the testing issue has been a difficult one for lawmakers to
resolve.
   Labor groups contend the testing _ particularly random
examinations of workers _ would violate privacy and could be
vulnerable to erroneous laboratory results that would jeopardize
employees' jobs.
   There are also differences over whether rehabilitation programs
should be provided for workers with drug or alcohol problems, who
would pay for them and whether employees who go through them should
be guaranteed getting their jobs back.
   ``How far we're going to be able to go, I don't know,'' Mineta
said late last week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
