<DOCNO> AP881009-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 1157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia-Future Bjt   10-09 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia-Future, Bjt,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ethnic, Economic Unrest Prompt Cries For Strong Leader</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethnic and economic unrest is
destroying the legacy of the late Josip Broz Tito, chipping away at
the power of the Communist Party and leaving many people clamoring
for another strong leader.
   Serbian nationalist rallies that brought hundreds of thousands
to the streets in recent weeks have turned into anti-government
protests by workers chanting that they cannot feed their families
and students demanding a multiparty system and free elections.
   ``The country is ruled by fascists!'' one student told an
anti-government protest in Montenegro last week.
   Just a year ago, such a statement immediately would have brought
the student a lengthy term in jail.
   But the worst economic and political crisis since World War II
has weakened the power of Communist authorities so much that such
declarations and acts of resurgent nationalism are now common.
   Symbols of royalist, pre-Communist Serbia have appeared as
graffiti on Belgrade streets. Songs from the same period, banned
just months ago, are sung openly in restaurants.
   The system Tito bequeathed to Yugoslavia when he died in 1980
was designed to keep this nationalism in check.
   By giving each of Yugoslavia's six republics and two autonomous
provinces broad control of their own affairs and rotating national
offices annually among Communists from the different regions, Tito
prevented one republic from dominating the others.
   But the ethnic splits in this nation of 23 million and the
yawning economic gap between the prosperous north and backward
south have combined to weaken the federal system, so it is
incapable of dealing with the worsening economic crisis.
   Inflation is at 217 percent, unemployment at 15 percent and the
foreign debt at $21 billion. Austerity measures imposed in May to
ensure more foreign loans have slashed wages but not prices, making
life hard for many workers and driving them into strikes and
protests.
   As economic hardship increases, nationalist sentiments grow.
People who thought of themselves as Yugoslav in better times now
think of themselves more as Serbs, Slovenes or Croats and angrily
blame other republics for their own economic demise.
   In Serbia this summer, this nationalist sentiment exploded into
a series of rallies fueled by Serbian discontent over the treatment
of their brethren in Kosovo, an autonomous Serbian province now
dominated by ethnic Albanians.
   The Serbian minority in Kosovo, once the heart of Serbia's
medieval empire, alleges daily harassment by Albanians, 90 percent
of the population. Serbs accuse the majority of seeking union with
neighboring Albania.
   The Serbian rallies quickly turned into a huge show of support
for Serbian Communist Party leader Slobodan Milosevic, an ambitious
47-year-old politician who has dominated Serbia's politics and
media for the past year.
   Milosevic has won popularity by pushing for greater Serbian
control over its two autonomous provinces, Vojvodina and Kosovo.
   On Thursday, a combination of his pressure and a 30-hour siege
by tens of thousands at local Communist Party headquarters forced
the resignation of Vojvodina's leadership.
   When demonstrators tried to do the same thing in the southern
republic of Montenegro on Friday night, club-wielding police waded
in to break up the crowd. Police used tear gas in another town in
Montenegro, and authorities clearly feared the unrest was getting
out of hand.
   Many Yugoslavs feel a strong leader like Tito is needed to
control the bubbling ethnic and economic tension. For the Serbs,
Milosevic is such a man, a dynamic speaker who last week
demonstrated his oratorical skills by persuading angry workers
outside the national Parliament to go home.
   But the westward-looking, most prosperous republics of Slovenia
and Croatia will oppose any Serb becoming a leader, and they are
alarmed by Milosevic's use of street rallies to pursue his
political aims.
   The Slovenes also fear another option _ military rule.
   ``We must stop the method of the lynch and more sharply discuss
the responsbility of all of us in legal institutions,'' Slovene
Communist Franc Setinc said in an interview published Sunday.
   Setinc resigned two weeks ago from the Communist Party's ruling
Politburo after coming under heavy fire in media controlled by
Milosevic.
   In Sunday's interview in Tanjug, without mentioning Milosevic by
name, he noted that the unrest is fueled by spontaneous
dissatisfaction over Kosovo, the economy and the Communist Party,
but is not unorganized.
   ``I am not trying to undermine anyone, but I am afraid of the
directors in the wings and their plans. Where is all this leading
us?''
</TEXT>
