<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Teacher-Slur     10-09 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Teacher-Slur,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Children Reverse Parents' Drive And Get Teacher Back</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents of grafs 2 and 15 may be objectionable.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>GOULD, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A white librarian who was dismissed for using
a racial slur before a class in an almost all-black district has
been taken back by the school district after her students decided
they wanted her to stay.
   The Gould School Board dismissed Lois Bostic after she used a
phrase including ``nigger'' while trying to control a class of
sixth-graders.
   Two of the district's 147 students are white.
   ``She didn't mean any harm to it,'' Ray Rainey Jr., Gould High
School senior class president, said Friday while he and other
students celebrated the board's reversal.
   The school board, reacting to a petition signed by 91 parents,
had asked Mrs. Bostic to resign by the week's end.
   But on Wednesday, six students gathered in the library to
discuss the situation.
   ``We decided we wanted her to stay,'' Rainey said.
   The students typed petitions and handed them out, and of the 135
students present Thursday, 124 signed.
   ``I think the parents signed their petition without really
knowing what it was about,'' Rainey said. ``They didn't know Mrs.
Bostic,'' he said of the parents.
   ``My aunt was the one that started the first petition,'' Rainey
said. `But my father said to do what I felt was right.''
   Alan Minor, school board president, was surprised by the
students' efforts.
   ``I thought there had been anger and animosity among the
students,'' he said. Instead, ``the anger came exclusively from the
parents.''
   Mrs. Bostic was overwhelmed by the students' reaction.
   ``I was dumbfounded when I found out how many students signed,''
she said.
   Mrs. Bostic, who is in her first year at the community of 1,670
in southeastern Arkansas, said she had heard the word nigger used
in conversation between two black students and got the impression
that it was acceptable among them.
   She also said she used the word for shock value to try to get
through to the students.
   Rainey said most students didn't take offense.
   ``She was saying not to act that way,'' he said.
   ``I've become a hero for this,'' Mrs. Bostic said. ``And it's
not right, because I made a stupid mistake.''
</TEXT>
