<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Election Bjt   10-09 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Election, Bjt,0748</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mulroney Hits Campaign Trail Looking for Free Trade Mandate</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney is leaving little
to chance while he campaigns for a Progressive Conservative Party
victory and for implementing a free trade agreement with the United
States.
   The prime minister's opponents in the heated three-way race for
the Nov. 21 election say a Mulroney victory would mean nothing less
than selling out Canada to its more powerful and richer neighbor.
   The traditional rough-and-tumble of Canadian campaigning was
altered this year by Mulroney's insistence on carefully controlled
public appearances and, at least in the first week of the campaign,
only rare departures from the script.
   Mulroney's two opponents describe their efforts to block the
free trade agreement his government negotiated with the United
States as the fight of the century.
   The deal would eliminate all tariffs between the two countries
end eventually put Canada's 26 million people in open competition
with the 245 million people of the United States. It would mean the
dismantling of a system of high tariffs that dates back to the 19th
century.
   ``It's a cause of my life to save Canada from this deal,''
Liberal Party leader John Turner has told Canadians. ``This is more
than an election. It is your future.''
   Ed Broadbent of the socialist New Democratic Party has
reiterated his party's traditional stand against free trade
agreements.
   Early polls show the Progressive Conservatives ahead in the
campaign, which Mulroney insists should not be simply a referendum
on the trade issue but rather an endorsement of his record during
four years of national leadership.
   The prime minister has the advantage of prosperity during his
administration and optimistic economic forecasts. The unemployment
rate for September, announced Friday, showed a further decrease
from 8 percent to 7.8 percent, considered low for Canada.
   A Gallup Poll taken during the 48 hours after Mulroney called
the election Oct. 1 indicated the Conservatives with 43 percent
support, Liberals with 33 percent and New Democrats with 22 percent.
   Such an outcome could give the Conservatives 295 seats in the
House of Commons, up from the 208 seats they held in the 282-member
House that was just dissolved. The Liberals held 40 seats and the
New Democrats had 33 with one vacancy.
   ``Given the volatility, given the fickleness of Canadian voters,
it's possible the Conservatives can stumble and lose their lead,''
said Sylvia Bashevkin, a political science professor at the
University of Toronto.
   Ms. Bashevkin, who is writing a book about Canadian nationalism,
said in an interview that the intensity of the free trade
discussion is rooted in ``a visceral issue in Canadian society'' _
that the larger, more powerful United States could overwhelm huge
but sparsely populated Canada.
   ``Nationalists of all sorts unite to speak out against any loss
of sovereignty,'' Ms. Bashevkin said.
   Opponents of the free trade agreement raise a range of fears
from environmental dangers and the exploitation of energy resources
to the potential loss of a fragile national identity. They also see
threats to Canada's extensive health care and social service
network.
   At the heart of the debate are fears that what is considered a
more aggressive American lifestyle could move north, pushing aside
Canadian traditions that value a sense of community.
   Mulroney says the fears are unjustified. Charging the opposition
with pursuing ``some nostalgic version of a past that perhaps never
existed,'' he says the creation of a larger North American market
is needed to assure Canada's future prosperity.
   A Conservative majority in the next Parliament would remove any
remaining blocks to the creation of a North American free trade
zone on Jan. 1.
   Both opposition parties say they would tear up the deal.
   The U.S. Senate approved the agreement with Canada, the United
States' top trading partner, by 83-9 last month. At least 70
percent of the $150 billion in trade each year between the
countries already is tariff-free.
   The Gallup Poll found free trade to be the dominant issue among
Canadian voters.
   Mulroney, 49, is a former corporate lawyer and leader of his
party since 1983.
   Although scandals that touched eight of his ministers reduced
the Conservatives' standing in the polls sharply during the first
three years of his term, Mulroney appears to have distanced himself
from those troubles and surged ahead.
</TEXT>
