<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Anti-SemiticLetter     10-09 0261</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Anti-Semitic Letter,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Anti-Semitic Letter Provokes Long Island Conservatives</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Suffolk County district attorney's office is
investigating the origin of an anti-Semitic letter that has
embroiled leaders of the Conservative Party in internal strife.
   The Long Island county's Conservative Party chairman, Pasquale
J. Curcio, apologized Friday to the American Jewish Congress for
the unsigned letter, which urged the defeat of two judgeship
candidates because they are Jewish.
   ``It turns my stomach,'' said Curcio, who was elected chairman
Oct. 2. ``The Conservative Party is not anti-Semitic and we had
nothing to do with that.''
   Curcio and the party's vice chairman, John Andrew Kay, accused
former party chairwoman Elaine Leirer of writing the letter, which
Curcio said was mailed to at least a dozen Conservative Party
members before the September primary election.
   Mrs. Leirer, who lost her chairmanship in a bitter battle with
Curcio and Kay, strongly denied having written the letter and said
the two men wrote it to discredit her. They denied the charge.
   The letter, written on plain stationery under the heading
``Official Conservative Announcement from the Chairwoman,'' urged
party members to vote for four non-Jewish candidates for judgeships.
   ``Do not let the Jews run Suffolk County,'' it concluded. ``Stay
with the chairwoman. Reject Jew lovers Curcio and Kay.''
   Both of the judicial candidates named in the letter, David
Freundlich and Morton Weissman, won their Conservative Party
primaries and are also running as Republicans in the general
election.
   The chief of the district attorney's rackets bureau, John E.
Holownia, said the letter was being investigated.
</TEXT>
