<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 1335EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SellingSoy     10-09 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Selling Soy,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>From Italians To Russians, They Come To See U.S. Soybean Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paola Ricas will return to Italy to
describe in her gourmet magazine foods made from U.S. soybeans.
N.G. Myndru will return to his farm in the Soviet Union to oversee
livestock feeding trials using U.S. soybean meal.
   Product promotion, including sponsoring visits by Italian food
journalists and Soviet agricultural experts, is a key feature of
the U.S. soybean industry.
   ``We raise high quality grain here in Illinois and we hope we
can meet your needs _ for your people and your diet,'' Champaign
County farmer Lee Eichhorst said at a recent dinner honoring
visiting Soviets.
   Money contributed by farmers enables the American Soybean
Association to carry out a wide range of programs aimed at creating
new uses and markets for American soybeans. Some money also comes
from the U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   ``We have invited the Italian food journalists to the States to
acquaint them with soybeans, and hopefully they will go home and
write about them,'' said ASA official Roger Leysen, who was
visiting Illinois but is based in Belgium.
   Ms. Ricas, editor of La Cucina Italiana, was especially
interested in new foods made from soy.
   ``I saw the pizza with the soybean flour and the ice cream,''
she said. ``This is new, and it is very important to me to taste
these things.''
   The Italian journalists visited a farm where soybeans are grown,
the Chicago Board of Trade where beans are bought and sold, a
factory that makes salad dressing, University of Illinois
laboratories where new soy foods are developed, supermarkets and
export facilities.
   The idea is to show potential customers that the United States
is the largest and most reliable soybean supplier. Illinois is the
nation's No. 1 soybean state.
   ``The Italians are growing soybeans but not enough to meet their
demand,'' Leysen said. ``We still need publicity in Italy to
increase demand even more.''
   However, the major use of soybeans is in livestock rations, and
ASA has been conducting feeding demonstrations on large cooperative
farms in the Soviet Union.
   Soy meal is added to Soviet corn, which is chopped and fed green
because their growing season is too short to produce mature ears of
corn.
   ``The tests showed the ASA formula worked,'' said Mansfield
farmer Ken Dalenberg, noting faster weight gain and better quality
meat compared with the traditional Soviet diet for hogs. ``These
promotions and feeding trials should build markets for U.S.
soybeans.''
   The Soviets, including top officials from huge state and
cooperative farms where feeding tests are conducted, came to the
United States to see how farmers raise soybeans and hogs.
   ``We are all involved in the production of something very
necessary for this world _ food,'' said Myndru, chairman of a
50,000-acre cooperative farm and member of the Supreme Soviet. ``We
are ... doing our best to get good results like you. If a farmer is
good, we say he is like an American farmer.''
   Myndru encouraged exchange visits between American and Soviet
farmers and agricultural researchers.
   Aleks Cerne, associate director of the ASA office in Vienna,
travelled with the Soviets. He said there is a great potential for
increased soybean sales to the Soviet Union, but cautioned that it
will take time and cooperation.
   ``Markets will come very slowly, but trade is a two-way
street,'' Cerne said. ``We sell them 10 times as much agricultural
product as we buy from them.''
</TEXT>
