<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     10-09 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Year With Indian Peacekeeping Soldiers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAFFNA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indian peacekeeping forces landed on
this island nation one year ago to try to end fighting by minority
Tamils demanding an independent state. Once regarded as heroes, the
Indians have become the enemy.
   ``When we saw the Indian troops arrive here, we greeted them
with garlands as our saviors,'' said Parameswari, a Tamil housewife
who spoke on condition that her family name not be used.
   ``We realized our mistake,'' she said. ``The Indians launched an
operation not only to kill the Tamil Tigers, but Tamil civilians.''
   Jaffna, about 165 miles north of the capital of Colombo, is a
city under siege.
   On Oct. 3, two pistol shots fired near a crowded bus stop killed
two young Tamil men. The streets emptied as Indian troops dressed
in camouflage gear drove into the city in military vehicles and
retrieved the bodies.
   The next day, three Indian soldiers died when a booby-trapped
bicycle exploded. Indian troops retaliated by shooting and killing
a young Tamil fleeing the scene.
   A group of Tamil boys, about 12 years old, ran through the
streets warning residents: ``Do not allow anybody to go into the
town. The Indians are coming.''
   ``We have gone through World War I and now we are in the midst
of World War II,'' said one Tamil woman, who did not want her name
used.
   The presidents of Sri Lanka and India _ which became involved in
the conflict because of its own 60 million Tamils _ signed an
accord July 29, 1987, aimed at ending the 5-year-old campaign by
militant Tamils for a separate nation in the northern and eastern
provinces.
   The mostly Hindu Tamils, 18 percent of the island's 16 million
people, claim they are discriminated against by the majority
Buddhist Sinhalese, who comprise 75 percent of the population and
control the government and the military.
   An estimated 8,500 people have died since the insurgency began
in 1983, including an estimated 1,000 civilians and at least 625
Indian soldiers.
   The peace accord was aimed at giving the Tamils more autonomy in
exchange for laying down arms.
   On Oct. 10, 1987, the first of an estimated 50,000 Indian troops
arrived in Sri Lanka across the Palk Straits, a waterway off the
southeast coast of India that separates the countries. The soldiers
were ordered to neutralize the most powerful of the rebel groups,
the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Ealam, who rejected the peace accord.
   An estimated 47,000 Indian soldiers remain in Sri Lanka, and the
Indian government says they will stay there until Sri Lanka's
president, Junius R. Jayewardene, says they are not needed.
   Tamils in Jaffna have mixed feeling about the presence of the
peacekeeping forces _ many want the Indians to leave, but others
aren't sure.
   ``They have been here for the past 12 months and our problems
have become worse. What will happen if they leave is anybody's
guess,'' said Sinnathamby Murugaveli, a student at Jaffna
University.
   Some Sri Lankans fear that if the Indian soldiers leave, they
will leave behind arms for some of the six moderate Tamil groups
who have helped hunt down the Tigers.
   ``This will lead to a fresh bout of bloodletting, giving an
excuse for the Sri Lankan armed forces to take over where the
Indians left, leaving us Tamils back at square one,'' said a
professor at Jaffna University, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
