<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle-DebateAftermath 2ndLd-Writethru a0696 10-09 0852</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Debate Aftermath, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0696,830</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post-Debate Quayle Says He's Become GOP `Lightning Rod'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf: Republican pollster ....; to CORRECT that
Phillips is a Republican political analyst.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN PUTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Quayle was supposed to show the country
last week that he ``has no horns,'' as one adviser said. Instead,
the Republican vice presidential nominee remains the most
controversial candidate on either party's ticket.
   He admitted as much when he observed Friday that he had become
``the lightning rod for the campaign.''
   Aides say Quayle's debate with Democratic rival Lloyd Bentsen, a
confrontation many voters seem to think Quayle lost, has not
affected the campaign strategy for the Indiana senator or his
relationship with GOP nominee George Bush.
   But some Bush aides have been quoted as saying privately that
his debate performance was assessed as a negative. Bush himself
rarely mentions Quayle during campaign appearances unless he is
responding to reporters' questions.
   Conservative Republican political analyst Kevin Phillips,
interviewed Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said there is no
doubt that voters, including many Republicans, are ``nervous''
about Quayle.
   ``It's very clear that the Democrats did get a dynamic out of
the Bentsen-Quayle debate,'' Phillips said. ``The question is how
much the Democrats, whose campaign strategy so far this year has
often been somewhat inept, can take advantage of that opening.''
   Democratic pollster Peter Hart, interviewed on the same show,
said comparisons of public and private polls before and after the
debate show a nationwide switch of 2 or 3 percentage points in
favor of the Democratic ticket.
   During an impromptu news conference on his campaign plane late
Friday, Quayle rejected suggestions that he is viewed as a
liability by the Bush camp.
   ``I'd like to find out who did say that,'' he said. ``I think I
might have some influence on their job security.''
   As for Bush, ``I don't know how he could have defended me any
more vigorously,'' Quayle said.
   ``He thought the debate was outstanding. He called me right
after the debate and he said `home run _ an absolute home run! And
he believes that and still believes that. ... I don't know how he
could be any more vigorous in his support.''
   Some GOP officials have seen Quayle, 41, as a liability almost
from the moment he was selected by Bush at the party convention in
New Orleans in mid-August.
   Intense media focus on his military service, academic record and
personal life, combined with his youth and his tendency to
misspeak, created the image of a lightweight candidate, especially
when compared with the patrician, 67-year-old Bentsen.
   Bush campaign chairman James A. Baker III told reporters before
the Oct. 5 debate in Omaha, Neb., that Quayle would have to show
millions of television viewers that he ``has no horns'' and was
``steady, serious and substantive.''
   Quayle generally performed well, although he seemed stumbling
and hesitant when asked repeatedly what he would do if he had to
assume the presidency.
   Democrats immediately capitalized on that with two TV ads, one
depicting Bush advisers regretting the choice of Quayle and another
conjuring up the specter of a Quayle presidency.
   Quayle responded by telling reporters that his new campaign role
was to take the heat for Bush and that in any event, the voters
ultimately choose between Bush and Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis, not their running mates.
   Quayle insisted that he _ not Bush's campaign strategists _ had
assigned him the role of lightning rod.
   ``I'm going to take all the heat and that's just fine. We'll let
George Bush have a free ride,'' he said.
   Asked why Bush was not the one to respond to the ads, Quayle
replied, ``They're attacking me.''
   Whether the debate will prove to be any sort of campaign
watershed remains to be seen. Aides say their strategy remains the
same.
   Quayle will continue to campaign in the party's traditional base
as well as key swing states such as Michigan and Ohio, which he
will visit this week. He will continue to raise money for the
ticket, court local and regional media coverage and make Dukakis
his primary target for attack.
   If anything, aides say, Quayle's campaign schedule will get
busier between now and Nov. 8.
   ``This guy is going to be playing a major role in helping this
ticket get elected,'' said David Prosperi, Quayle's spokesman.
``This is the big run for the finish line.''
   Quayle's reception on his post-debate campaign travels has been
good, although he has appeared mostly at college and high school
events that resemble student pep rallies.
   Bush's running mate seems more relaxed around reporters since
the debate, although he makes no secret of his resentments over
press coverage of his campaign.
   He playfully turned a paint sprayer on reporters as he toured a
Chattanooga, Tenn., technical school recently. ``That's for all
those articles you've written about me,'' he said.
   But Quayle didn't seem flustered during his airborne session
with reporters Friday, even though the exchange was testy at times.
``I figured out, you weren't all that bad,'' he told them.
</TEXT>
