<1ST_LINE>r a AM-GuardsShot     10-09 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Guards Shot,0285</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Public Housing Residents Cheer Shooting of Guards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of a crime-ridden public
housing project cheered when the body of a security guard was
carried to an ambulance after he was gunned down in a hail of
bullets.
   ``When they brought (him) out, people started clapping and
saying, `Hurrah,''' said Acorn housing complex resident Gustina
Hamilton, 51.
   A second guard remained in critical condition Sunday following
the attack by several men who sprayed the complex's security office
with bullets from assault-style weapons, police said. As many as 60
bullets were pumped into the room within two minutes during the
assault Friday night.
   ``When I heard one guard had been killed, I didn't feel anything
whatsoever and I know this is wrong,'' added Hamilton, who said her
son was hurt in a scuffle with guards two months ago.
   Residents of the 673-unit complex have been complaining for a
year that guards hired by Prostaf Security to chase out drug
dealers have instead brutalized residents.
   In August of last year, about 80 people signed a petition
alleging that guards had beaten at least 12 residents and otherwise
harassed them, particularly after management imposed an 11 p.m.
curfew in an effort to curtail crime.
   Police said they had no suspects in the death of guard Reese
Howard Davis, 23, of Concord. Davis was pronounced dead of multiple
gunshot wounds on arrival at Highland Hospital.
   Critically wounded was Wale U. Osijo, 33, whose hospital
location was being kept secret. Another guard in the office at the
time of the shooting was uninjured.
   An unidentified resident told reporters shots had been fired at
security guards before.
</TEXT>
