<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Latvia     10-09 0613</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Latvia,0639</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crowd Prays For Nationalist Group In First Cathedral Service In 30
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities on Sunday allowed the first religious
service in 30 years in a Latvian cathedral converted into a concert
hall, and an overflow crowd prayed for a new nationalist group.
   The service was in the 13th Century Dom Cathedral, also known as
St. Peter's Cathedral, in Riga, the capital of the republic of
Latvia.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, and Ingrid Titavs, who
attended the service, said a Lutheran pastor devoted prayers to the
People's Front. The group, which demands that Latvians have more
say over their religious, economic and cultural affairs, ended its
founding congress Sunday.
   Ms. Titavs, a member of another group called the Latvian
National Independence Movement, said by telephone from Riga that
state-run television broke with its usual policy of promoting
atheism to carry the end of the service live.
   She said a long line of people waited to get inside the church
and a huge crowd stood outside during the service because there was
no more room for them inside. Police did not interfere, as they
have at other religious gatherings, she said.
   The cathedral, begun in 1211, is the largest in the Baltic Sea
republics of Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia. The Soviet Union's
atheistic communist government had the building turned into a
concert hall about 30 years ago.
   Tass implied Sunday that the conversion was not done for
political reasons. It said the state took control of the cathedral
``because the small parish appeared to be unable to keep up this
architectural monument in due order.''
   The People's Front, which claims 130,000 members, ended a
two-day conference in Riga by adopting a charter, resolutions and
electing its leaders, Tass said.
   Neither Ms. Titavs nor Tass provided details of the measures.
The front has been pushing to make the republic economically
autonomous from Moscow.
   Ms. Titavs, who monitored broadcasts of Sunday's debate, said
the session was ``very stormy, very democratic and very open.''
   She said many speakers complained about the Latvian Communist
Party and government. The republic's president and Communist Party
chief were replaced last week.
   Speakers also condemned the Soviet takeover of the Baltic
republic in 1940, Ms. Titavs said. Latvia, Estonia and Lithuania
were absorbed by the Soviet Union under a pact signed with Nazi
Germany.
   ``Very many said we should have the right to be free,'' the
activist said.
   The People's Front is similar to organizations formed in
neighboring Estonia and Lithuania to make nationalist demands and
push Mikhail S. Gorbachev's program to reform the economy and
society.
   Tass said that among those attending the sessions in Riga were
the new president of the republic, Anatoly Gorbunov, who assumed
his post Thursday. His presence lent the group some official
backing.
   Jan Vagris, who took over as Latvia's Communist Party first
secretary on Tuesday, told Soviet television in an interview
broadcast Sunday night that he supports the People's Front because
it is firmly behind Gorbachev's reforms.
   In other nationalist activity, activists campaigning for the
independence of the republic of Georgia in the Caucasus Mountains
staged a four-hour sit-in Sunday.
   A witness, speaking by telephone from the Georgian capital of
Tbilisi, said several dozen people sat near the city's KGB
headquarters and carried the flag that flew in the republic before
it was made part of the Soviet Union.
   They also held signs demanding freedom of speech and protesting
police confiscation of an underground journal, said the witness,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Plainclothes KGB officers ripped away some of the signs, he
said. But the demonstrators dispersed voluntarily after authorities
promised to return the journal copies.
</TEXT>
