<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SlurApology     10-09 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Slur Apology,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Candidate Apologizes For Campaign Slur</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Democratic candidate Brian Moss
says he did not intend to offend anyone when he said that
``polacks, spiks, wops and the Irish'' are welcome in the
Democratic Party.
   Moss made the comment after criticizing his opponent, Sen. Orrin
Hatch, R-Utah, for an earlier statement that the Democrats are
``the party of homosexuals.''
   Almost immediately after his speech last week at the University
of Utah, Moss began receiving complaints from students, Hatch
campaign aides and others who found his offhand remark offensive.
   Moss is a Salt Lake City businessman, a former unsuccessful
candidate for Utah state treasurer and the son of former Sen. Frank
Moss, D-Utah, whom Hatch defeated in 1976.
   Moss said the Democratic Party was willing to listen to the
concerns of diverse groups such as homosexuals and other
minorities, even though it may not agree with them.
   ``We have been the party of the blacks, the browns, of the
Asian-Americans, of the young, of the old, of the poor. We're the
party of the of immigrants,'' he said.
   ``You may call us the party of the polacks, the party of spiks,
the party of wops, the party of the Irish ... any of those names,
because the Democratic Party has always had a tent large enough to
welcome all of those groups who are seeking their civil rights and
their concerns,'' he said.
   Moss said later he used those words to illustrate the
``harshness'' of Hatch's earlier ``inflammatory language.''
   ``It was rash. And for that I have apologized, will apologize
and will continue to apologize,'' Moss said.
   Hatch campaign manager Bud Scruggs accused Moss of ``focusing on
peripheral matters'' instead of dealing with the substance of
Hatch's point ``that the national Democratic leadership is beholden
to left-wing groups.''
   Scruggs said that ``for Brian Moss to try to turn that point
into a racial slur is kind of one more notch down in his level of
respectability in conducting the campaign.''
</TEXT>
