<HEAD>Iraqis To Build New Presidential Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq will build a new presidential palace
to symbolize ``the heroic sacrifices of the Iraqi people'' in the
8-year-old war against Iran, the government-run Baghdad Observer
daily said Sunday.
   The new palace will replace the one built on the banks of the
Tigris River for Iraq's last monarch, King Faisal II, in 1956, two
years before he was killed in a coup.
   The English-language daily said the new structure will be built
on an elevated area of 430 square yards and will be surrounded by
green fields and orchards.
   The paper said several Iraqi and other Arab engineering
consultants have submitted designs for the new palace.
   The Baghdad Observer said President Saddam Hussein has ordered
that the design of his new palace be on historical Arab
architectural lines.
   ``It will tell the coming generations that Iraq has done a lot
to serve the Arab nation,'' the daily quoted Saddam as telling
engineers who participated in a design competition.
   The paper also said that Saddam ordered that some of the gold
donated by Iraqis for the war effort be used for ornamental
decorations on the new palace's main gate.
   Weapons used by Iraqi soldiers will be part of a steel monument
in the planned palace.
   The paper did not say how much the new palace will cost or when
construction would start.
</TEXT>
