<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ElectricBoat-Strike     10-09 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Electric Boat-Strike,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tentative Agreement Could End Shipyard Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GROTON, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Union members at the Electric Boat shipyard
plan to vote Tuesday on a tentative contract agreement that would
end a strike for more than 10,000 employees.
   Negotiators for the company and its workers reached the
agreement Saturday, the 100th day of a walkout by the submarine
builders.
   Electric Boat is the Navy's sole producer of the giant Trident
nuclear submarines and competes annually with the Newport News
(Va.) Shipbuilding & Drydock Co. for contracts to build the
smaller, SSN-688 fast attack subs.
   The company and the Metal Trades Council reached the tentative
settlement following four days of negotiations.
   ``We will unanimously endorse this agreement and recommend to
our membership that they ratify it,'' said MTC President Joseph W.
Messier.
   Messier and chief negotiator Thomas E. Kelly both refused to
discuss details of the contract.
   The company's last known four-year offer included a bonus worth
5 percent of a worker's annual pay in the first year; a 4 percent
bonus in the second year; a 3 percent general wage increase the
third year; and a $600 bonus in the fourth year. The proposal also
included a $1,000 contract ratification bonus.
   The MTC, which represents 10 local trades unions, struck July 1
when Electric Boat proposed a new contract that included only
bonuses and no raises over three years. Workers rejected the
proposal by a ratio of 5-3 on June 30.
</TEXT>
