<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionWars     10-09 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Wars,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Atlanta Looks to Processing `Operation Rescue' Prisoners</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The so-called ``Siege of Atlanta'' anti-abortion
demonstrations are over but the city is still dealing with scores
of people clogging the jails and courts, many refusing to give
their names.
   One ``John Doe'' inmate jailed since July 19 escaped Saturday,
but police know his real name and where he lives.
   Last week's five days of protests outside four clinics ended
Saturday with the arrest of 40 demonstrators, bringing the week's
total to 461.
   About 140 of those still jailed have applied for release on bond
but have not been processed, said Tom Pocock, deputy director of
the Atlanta Corrections Bureau.
   Some applications were processed Sunday and by late afternoon
the number of protesters still jailed was down to 319, jail
officials said.
   Operation Rescue, the New York-based group that organized the
protests that began during the Democratic National Convention, has
accused the city of purposely delaying the releases to keep the
demonstrators in jail until the organizers leave.
   The city responds that Operation Rescue boasted that it would
clog the city's judicial process with hundreds of arrests and says
the demonstrators succeeded in doing just that.
   The city has refused to separate the paperwork of Operation
Rescue prisoners from that of the rest of the jail population,
further delaying processing.
   ``We have asked that Operation Rescue designate to us who should
be bonded out first based on family, job or health concerns,''
Pocock said Saturday.
   Many of those arrested identify themselves only as ``Baby Jane
Doe'' or ``Baby John Doe'' in solidarity with aborted fetuses and
cannot be freed on bond, the city says, because they could not be
found if they refused to appear.
   Baby John Doe No. 1, arrested at the first Operation Rescue
demonstration on July 19, escaped Saturday from a mimimum-security
jail annex. Pocock said the city lacked the resources or the
apparent need for better security and said the prisoner had assured
police he would be no trouble.
   He said police are seeking Joseph Roach, 50, of Broomall, Pa.,
and will charge him with escape. ``He exploited our benevolence,''
Pocock said.
   Since Operation Rescue came to Atlanta in July for the
Democratic National Convention, police have arrested more than
1,200 demonstrators.
   City officials said they had spent more than $500,000 on
security, arrests, jail and court costs for the protests before
last week's demonstrations. The police academy had to be closed and
recruits used to help control the demonstrators and keep the
clinics open.
   When last week's protests started Tuesday, police used
rougher-than-usual tactics, dragging demonstrators to buses if they
refused to walk. They eased up at midweek after several complaints.
   Operation Rescue has called for a nationwide demonstration Oct.
29.
   The aim of last week's demonstrations was to block clinic
entrances to prevent or dissuade women from entering to have
abortions, but many women entered the clinics anyway.
   Clinic operators said most appointments were kept, and some
patients entered before dawn to avoid the pickets.
</TEXT>
