<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 2ndLd-Writethru a0729 10-09 0663</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0729,0683</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Palestinians Killed As Army Hunts Agitators</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with 3 Palestinians killed,
details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Palestinians were shot to death as army
units hunted down agitators in 30 villages Sunday, while businesses
shut across the occupied territories in a strike marking 10 months
of rebellion against Israeli rule.
   Israeli troops shot and wounded at least 22 Palestinians in
clashes, Arab hospital officials said.
   The deaths raised to at least 294 the number of Palestinians
killed since the uprising was launched Dec. 8 against Israeli rule
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, seized from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 Middle East war. Six Israelis have died during the same
period.
   Most of the casualties Sunday were reported in West Bank
villages, where the raids were centered. Dozens of Palestinians
were arrested, witnesses said. They said troops removed rock and
barrel roadblocks and ordered anti-Israeli slogans washed from
village walls.
   A military official said the army sweep was ``part of our effort
to use different tactics'' to try to restore order in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   Israeli troops opened fire on a mob attacking them in the West
Bank village of Yatta when they entered to search and make arrests,
the official said. He said army helicopters evacuated the wounded
but two Palestinians died while receiving medical treatment.
   A third Palestinian was fatally shot in a skirmish with an
Israeli security guard, the army said.
   One of the dead, who was not identified by name, was wanted by
security forces for organizing protests, said the official,
speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The official said no figures were available on the number of
arrests. He confirmed two Palestinians were wounded and said other
reports of injuries still were being checked. Military sources
confirmed eight wounded.
   In the Gaza Strip, an Israeli security guard was attacked by a
man with a knife when he tried to check the man's identification
aboard a bus entering the border town of Rafah from Egypt, an army
official said.
   The guard opened fire, killing the man and wounding another
passenger, the official said. He said the guard suffered minor head
wounds.
   An Arab reporter identified the dead man as 20-year-old Osama
Ahmed Abu Dahi, a university student from Rafah.
   The army later clamped a curfew on the town of 11,000 to prevent
any backlash.
   The strike, called by the PLO-backed Unified National Leadership
of the Uprising, closed shops and businesses throughout the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   On the eve of the strike, 10 torches were lighted on Ibal Mount
overlooking Nablus, the West Bank's largest city with 120,000
residents. The torches were to symbolize the completed months of
the ``intefadeh,'' Arabic for uprising.
   Most of the casualties have occurred in clashes between
Palestinians and Israeli troops. Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin
said this weekend that more than 7,000 people have been injured in
the confrontations.
   In the last three days, more than 70 Palestinians have been
wounded in clashes in the occupied territories. Nine deaths have
been reported, including four Friday in stone-throwing melees in
Nablus.
   Seventeen of the injuries reported Sunday occurred in the West
Bank. Four were in the village of Kafr Nimeh, the site of a
day-long Israeli sweep, hospital officials said.
   In Gaza City, five Palestinians suffered gunshot wounds,
including a 13-year-old boy struck in the left hand, doctors at
Arab Ahli and Shifa hospitals reported.
   Clashes have intensified in recent weeks, and Israeli government
and military officials have accused the Palestinians of trying to
influence the upcoming Israeli elections and an expected meeting of
the Palestine Liberation Organization's parliament-in-exile.
   Security in the West Bank and Gaza has become a key issue in the
campaign leading to the Nov. 1 Israeli Parliament elections. The
PLO, meanwhile, is said to be split over what political moves to
make to enhance the uprising.
</TEXT>
