<HEAD>Libya Requests Immediate OPEC Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya on Sunday said the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries should meet immediately to come up with a plan
to restore falling oil prices.
   The official Libyan news agency JANA, monitored in Rome, said
Libya called for an urgent meeting of the OPEC Ministerial Council
to ``take the necessary measures to stop the fall in prices,
restore stability to the oil market and to take prices up to levels
that are fair both to consumer and producer.''
   Oil prices tumbled last week to the lowest level since 1986.
Most analysts blame the sharp decline on the continued high amounts
of Saudi Arabian crude flowing into the market.
   The price of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude,
fell Wednesday to $12.60.
   JANA said Libya's decision to call for the extraordinary meeting
was made ``after consultation with some (of the 13) OPEC member
countries.'' It did not elaborate.
