<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cloudy And Cool In The Northeast</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain was scattered across the eastern half of the nation Sunday,
and parts of the Northeast were touched by record low temperatures.
   Snow, occasionally mixed with rain, fell over northern Maine,
and changed to rain across the central section of the state by
noon. Two inches of snow fell on the top of Mount Washington, N.H.,
at over 6,000 feet, during the six hours up to 2 p.m. EDT.
   Light rain was scattered from western New York state across
northern Ohio, from southeastern Kansas into northwestern Arkansas,
and over central Louisiana into west-central Mississippi.
   Record lows were reported at Atlantic City, N.J., at 30 degrees;
Hartford, Conn., 28; Newark, N.J., 35; Syracuse, N.Y., 30;
Tallahassee, Fla., 38; and Wilmington, Del., 33. Records were tied
at Allentown, Pa., at 30; New York City, 37; Philadelphia, 35; and
Scranton, Pa., 31.
   But the official low in the 48 states was 16 at Gunnison, Colo.
   At the other extreme, Los Angeles hit a record 99 degrees at the
Civic Center.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 38
degrees at Limestone, Maine, to 100 at Thermal, Calif.
   For Monday, scattered showers were forecast over the lower Great
Lakes and across Upper Michigan, with sunshine over much of the
rest of the nation.
   High only in the 40s were predicted in northern New England; in
the 50s and 60s from central New England into South Carolina, from
inland sections of the central Gulf of Mexico states across the
Tennessee Valley, the Ohio Valley, the Great Lakes, the upper half
of the Mississippi Valley, the Missouri Valley and the northern
Plains; in the 60s over the southern Rockies and along the central
coast of California; in the 80s over much of Florida, across
southern Texas, much of the West between the Rockies and the Sierra
Nevada, and over much of the northern and southern Pacific Coast;
in the 90s to near 100 through the desert Southwest; and generally
in the 70s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
