<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UgandanChildren     10-09 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ugandan Children,0358</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ugandan Children Give Concert to Aid African Relief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLINTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The performers in the choir were children
who lost one or both parents in civil strife in Uganda. Some saw
their parents killed. Others wandered in the wilderness and went
hungry with no one to care for them.
   But as the African Children's Choir performed at Clinton Junior
High School Saturday, the singers showed none of the emotional
scars.
   ``If you came here to see a choir of long-faced, sad, orphan
children, you came to the wrong place,'' Gary Oliver, executive
director of the choir, told the audience of about 700.
   The choir is touring the nation to raise money to help build and
support orphanages and schools in Uganda.
   The children sang American spirituals such as ``Gospel Train''
and ``He's Got the Whole World in His Hands.'' They also performed
Christian songs in several African dialects.
   ``The Scriptures said, `A child shall lead them,''' the Rev.
Roger Tieken of Christ Lutheran Church said after the performance.
``These children led us all here today.''
   Many of the children lost their parents during the reign of Gen.
Idi Amin, who reportedly was responsible for jailing, torturing and
killing 500,000 Ugandans. Amin's regime, which began in 1971 when
he seized power from Prime Minister Milton Obote, was toppled in
1979, but reports of widespread violence and death were reported as
late as 1985.
   Despite the turmoil in their native country, the children said
they miss Uganda.
   ``I miss my mom and sisters,'' Richard Kaweesa, 12, said.
   ``I miss the people,'' said Florence Nalule.
   When the 26 children first came to America, about two-thirds did
not speak English, Oliver said. Today, they all speak English.
   ``It improves their employment opportunity in Uganda,'' Oliver
said.
   ``Home is home for them,'' Oliver said. ``They want to be with
their own people and eat their own food.''
   The children said they've enjoyed their stay in America and have
grown fond of pizza, Chinese food and hamburgers. But they said
don't like sandwiches, chocolate and unmelted cheese.
</TEXT>
