<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Thornburgh-Drugs     10-09 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thornburgh-Drugs,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Attorney General Blames Congress for Drug Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
blames Congress for problems in the battle against illegal drugs,
saying rhetoric is getting in the way of action.
   ``It's hard to remain patient when Congress seems to be waging
only a rhetorical war on drugs, denying year after year the
administration's requests for full funding for the necessary
resources to carry out our anti-drug efforts,'' Thornburgh said
Saturday.
   He told most of the nation's 94 U.S. attorneys gathered for a
meeting here that the war on drugs is one of the few areas where
Congress has shown budgetary restraint over the last seven years in
spite of a national consensus to do otherwise.
   Under fiscal 1989 appropriations, Congress has reduced U.S.
attorney positions by 10 percent, Thornburgh said. Legislators also
cut $321 million from President Reagan's request for new prisons,
providing for only two of seven proposed, he said.
   ``I will not be satisfied until we obtain full funding for our
efforts, until we put an end to the situation of a federal law
enforcement officer having to set aside a citizen's complaint,
saying, `Sorry, we don't have enough agents to check that out.' Or
of a U.S. attorney telling an agent, `Sorry, we don't have enough
prosecutors to bring that case to trial.' Or of a judge telling a
prosecutor that there is no room in a federal prison for a
convicted drug trafficker.''
   To that end, Thornburgh asked federal prosecutors to prepare
reports for him on the narcotics trafficking business in their
areas.
   ``Drag it out from under the rock where it lives and breeds so
that we can fully educate the American public as to the size and
breadth of these illegal and insidious business operations, so that
the public will better understand and more enthusiastically support
the difficult struggle in which we are engaged,'' he said.
   ``Furnish that information to me, and I promise you, that no one
will ever again accuse us of waging a phony war on drugs,''
Thornburgh pledged.
</TEXT>
