<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland     10-09 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland,0265</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says Solidarity Spokesman's U.S. Testimony Damaging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony by Solidarity spokesman Janusz
Onyskiewicz before a U.S. Congressional hearing has harmed Poland,
the foreign ministry said Sunday.
   The state news agency PAP said the foreign ministry has turned
over materials concerning last month's testimony to the prosecutor
general for legal review.
   ``There is no doubt, however, that from the political and moral
point of view the attitude of Janusz Onyskiewicz ... did some harm
to Poland abroad,'' the news agency said in a statement.
   Onyskiewicz, a mathematics instructor at Warsaw University who
has been Solidarity's spokesman since 1981, returned to Poland a
week ago after a trip to the United States. While in Washington, he
met President Reagan and appeared before a congressional hearing.
   During the visit, Onyskiewicz urged continued American pressure
on Poland to bring about legal recognition of Solidarity, the
Soviet bloc's first independent trade union, which was suppressed
by the martial law crackdown in 1981 and banned the next year.
   Onyskiewicz and Jan Nowak, director of the Polish-American
Congress, an organization of Americans of Polish descent, testified
before a congressional committee about human rights in Poland and
treatment of Poles elsewhere, including the Soviet Union.
   Sunday's statement said Onyskiewicz's testimony was
``unprecedented'' and marked the first time a Polish citizen
permanently residing in Poland had testified before a U.S.
Congressional hearing.
   Polish officials have often criticized U.S. aid given to
Solidarity over the last several years, saying it in effect makes
the banned union an agent of a foreign power.
</TEXT>
