<HEAD>Music Fans Paint the Town Blue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40,000 music fans showed up in this
Mississippi River town for the third annual King Biscuit Blues
Festival.
   ``A lot of people thought the blues were dead, but anyone who
was in town this weekend sure wouldn't believe that,'' said Bubba
Sullivan, owner of Blues Corner Records.
   And the maps in Sullivan's record store prove it.
   Sullivan asked customers to mark their hometowns on the United
States map with pins. By Saturday afternoon, the map was covered
with pins from Seattle to San Diego and from Connecticut to Florida.
   A world map next to it had pins in Germany, Japan, Austria and
New Zealand.
   The festival, which featured performances on a stage in front of
an old railroad station, started Friday night with J.E. Morgan, Mud
Boy and the Neutrons, C.W. Gatlin, and Levon Helm.
   On Saturday, the lineup included Lonnie Shields, the Jelly Roll
Kings, Sunnyland Slim and Kansas City Red. Also on tap were James
Cotton and a tribute to Muddy Waters featuring Pinetop Perkins,
Jimmy Rogers, Mojo Buford and the Legendary Blues Band.
   The festival was named after ``King Biscuit Time,'' a half-hour
blues program on a local radio station since 1941.
