<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Baby-HeartTransplant     10-09 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Baby-Heart Transplant,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couples Seeking Donor Hearts for their Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOMA LINDA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The director of Loma Linda
University's infant heart transplant program was joined Sunday by
two distraught sets of parents who pleaded for heart donors to save
their children.
   Daymon and Cynthia Petersen of Salt Lake City, Utah, joined
David and Susan Jirschefske of Pasadena, Calif., to ask parents of
infants who have died to consider donating the baby's organs.
   ``I just hope to God they can look through the pain,'' said
Daymon Petersen, whose unborn son has been diagnosed with
hypoplastic left-heart syndrome, a terminal underdevelopment of the
heart's left ventricle. The child is expected to be born in about
two weeks.
   ``Once he's born the time clock starts,'' Petersen said. ``And
you don't know when that clock will stop.''
   The Jirschefske's 1-week-old son Daniel also has been diagnosed
with the disease.
   ``People need to know that there is a desperate need for organs,
from the first day of life to adulthood,'' said Dr. Leonard Bailey,
head of Loma Linda University Medical Center's infant heart
transplant program.
   ``Any time there's a brain-dead baby _ which in itself is an
utterly hopeless tragedy _ that tragedy can be transformed into
life for as many as three or four other babies and children,''
Bailey said.
   Bailey in 1984 performed the controversial transplant of a
baboon heart to the infant known as Baby Fae, who died 20 days
after the surgery.
</TEXT>
