<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 2011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Polio     10-09 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Polio,0605</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nationwide Polio Vaccination Campaign Begins, Some Panic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel began a nationwide campaign Sunday to
vaccinate three-quarters of its population against polio after the
infectious virus was found in sewage in 27 areas. Panic was
reported at some vaccination centers.
   The Health Ministry ordered the campaign to vaccinate 3.2
million people after 10 Israelis were affected by the disease that
causes muscular paralysis, spokesman Shmuel Algrabli said.
   Last Friday, vaccinations began in a few areas where the virus
was found in sewage. The expanded national campaign was decided on
after the virus subsequently was discovered in other areas.
   Since September, polio has spread from central Israel to
Jerusalem, the port city of Haifa, and was found in sewage in at
least 12 cities from northern Tiberias to Deir el Balah in the
occupied Gaza Strip in the south.
   But Algrabli denied there was a polio epidemic. ``Experts say
it's only a local event. The situation has not changed for the
worse. We haven't had a single polio case since Sept. 12, and those
10 were mostly in one area.''
   About 3.2 million people under the age 40 are to be vaccinated
the next four weeks at the cost of at least $2.5 million. Those
over 40 are not included under the theory they would likely have
been innoculated during the polio scare in the 1940s and '50s.
   Sunday, the ministry began vaccinating infants of up to 2 months
old but in many areas, older children were also vaccinated.
   Algrabli said about 350,000 people were vaccinated Sunday.
   In many clinics, shortages were reported. In Yehud near Tel
Aviv, where the virus was found, a woman told Israel radio:
   ``I have been in the clinic since 8 a.m. We check every hour,
and they still have no vaccines.''
   At a mother-and-child care center in Jerusalem's Mahane Yehuda
market, nurses said they ran out of vaccines in the morning but
later received some supplies.
   Mothers stood in line with their children. One woman brought her
yet unnamed week-old niece straight from the hospital where she was
born.
   At some clinics panic was reported.
   Linda Cahill, who immunized her two children at the Misgav Ladah
Hospital in Jerusalem, said many adults crowded around nurses,
asking to be vaccinated. Some burst into tears when they learned
they could not be vaccinated with their children.
   The polio virus caught Israel unprepared. Israelis are immunized
as children and the current vaccination is viewed as an additional
booster. There were no polio cases in 1986 and only one case in
1987. Recent cases were blamed on overflowing sewage.
   ``Sewage is a time-bomb that can explode every moment,'' Health
Minister Shoshana Arbeli-Almozlino told Prime Minister Yitzhak
Shamir at a Cabinet meeting Sunday, according to Israel radio.
   Meanwhile, polio became an issue in Israel's elections campaign
as Amnon Rubinstein, head of the centrist Shinui movement, demanded
Arbeli-Almozlino resign. The health minister is running for
Parliament on the ticket of the left-leaning Labor Party.
   ``Why resign? Did I bring polio to Israel?'' Arbeli-Almozlino
was quoted as saying in the daily newspaper Yediot Ahronot.
   The Tourism Ministry expressed concern that reports about the
disease would keep tourists from Israel. Tourism already has
dropped dramatically since the Palestinian uprising broke out in
the occupied territories 10 months ago.
   ``There is no problem with visiting Israel. We welcome every
tourist. Those wishing to be vaccinated can do so at the same time
Israeli adults are called in,'' Algrabli said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881009-0069 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 2029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-BlackUnityVote     10-09 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Unity Vote,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meeting Fails to Focus Black Support on One Mayoral Candidate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An attempt to have Chicago's black community
unite behind one mayoral candidate yielded no clear winner as
delegates to a meeting showed strong support for two contenders.
   ``We are about to commit political fratricide and not have any
political power in this town anymore,'' said attorney Lewis Myer
Jr., who was the keynote speaker for Saturday's meeting.
   Aldermen Danny Davis, who has announced he is running for mayor,
and Timothy Evans, who is expected to enter the race, split the
vote of most of the 53 delegates from black organizations. Davis
garnered 24 votes, Evans got 23 and Mayor Eugene Sawyer got 6 votes.
   ``Unless we have unity we might as well hang it up today,'' said
the Rev. Willie Barrow, leader of Chicago's Operation PUSH.
   Chicago's election to replace the late Mayor Harold Washington,
who died last year, will either be next spring or in 1991. The date
is the subject of a lawsuit.
   An additional 118 black groups that were invited to take part in
the meeting either abstained or did not send representatives. No
current or anticipated mayoral candidates attended.
   The vote came at the second meeting designed to unify the black
community behind a single black candidate. The first gathering, at
which Davis spoke, was Aug. 27.
   Evans and Sawyer did not attend the first meeting, saying the
gathering was not representative of the entire city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
