<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Obit-Richardson     10-09 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Richardson,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sir Egerton Richardson, Former Ambassador To U.N. and U.S., Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Egerton Richardson, Jamaica's first
permanent representative to the United Nations and former
ambassador to the United States, has died at his home, authorities
said Sunday. He was 76 years old.
   The cause of his death Saturday night was not immediately known,
but Richardson had been ill for more than a year, weekend news
editor Wyvonyn Gager of the Daily Gleaner newspaper said.
   Richardson was born Aug. 12, 1912, and entered the civil service
in 1933. He was named Jamaica's first representative to the United
Nations in 1962, shortly after the island gained independence from
Great Britain, and occupied the post until 1967, when he was named
ambassador to the United States.
   Richardson remained ambassador in Washington until 1972.
   The diplomat attended Calabar High School in Kingston and
graduated from Oxford University in England.
   ``I had the pleasure of working with him for a number of years
and admired his competence,'' former Prime Minister Michael Manley
told the Kingston newspaper. ``He also had the unique ability of
being able to analyze the most complex of problems and present his
advice simply and concisely.''
   Richardson is survived by his wife, Ivonne, a son and a
daughter, whose names were not immediately known.
   Funeral arrangements were incomplete.
</TEXT>
