<HEAD>Dallas Temple, Mosque Vandalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Windows were shot out and slurs were spray painted
on a Jewish temple, a Jewish community center and a mosque,
extending a yearlong string of vandalism at religious institutions.
   ``I think it's fairly clear that all three episodes are related
and done roughly within the same time period,'' said Mark Briskman,
regional director of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith.
``That's clearly a rising of the level of the incidents _ that a
weapon was used to fire into the facilities.''
   The Mosque of Richardson, the Jewish Temple Shalom and the
Jewish Community Center were attacked sometime Saturday night,
police said.
   Vandals shot out windows and spray-painted red Nazi,
anti-Semitic and anti-Islamic slogans on all three buildings,
police said.
   Briskman said Jewish leaders believe a small group of white
supremacists, called skinheads because they shave their hair, may
be responsible for the attacks. Police are investigating.
   Since last November, at least eight minor anti-Semitic attacks
on Jewish institutions in Dallas have been reported to the
Anti-Defamation League.
