<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Burma     10-09 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Two In Capital; Rebels Say 1000s Of Students Join
Ranks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops killed two people Sunday, and
rebels said thousands of students have joined their ranks to fight
the authoritarian regime that has ruled Burma for 26 years.
   State-run Radio Rangoon said troops shot at six suspected drug
addicts said to be resisting arrest in a northeast suburb, killing
one. A second person was reported shot and killed when the suspect
ran off after being challenged during the dusk-to-dawn curfew still
in effect in the capital.
   Since seizing power Sept. 18, Gen. Saw Maung's military
government has said its forces killed 440 people, including killing
looters, gamblers, curfew- breakers and anti-government
demonstrators. Western diplomats believe the number is higher.
   Saw Maung moved to quell anti-government protests, beginning
late July, that attempted to topple the military leadership that
has wielded power in Burma since 1962.
   The new government has allowed nine mostly opposition parties to
form and promised general elections. But opposition leaders say
they doubt free and fair elections can be held under the repressive
system.
   Nearly 9,000 students and other Burmese have joined rebel groups
at bases along the Thai border seeking refuge and arms to fight
their repressive government, rebel officials said Sunday.
   Another 4,000 students from Rangoon and other major cities have
arrived at camps of the Karen National Union, the strongest
ethnic-based insurgency, said Karen spokeswoman Naw Lydia.
   The rebel groups have waged war for four decades against the
government, which they say has reneged on promises of autonomy for
their ethnically distinct areas. They control vast tracts of the
country.
</TEXT>
