<HEAD>Four Provincial Opposition Leaders Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ Four opposition leaders were
arrested, and two of them were beaten by soldiers, after a clash
between reformists and allies of the former Duvalier regime,
witnesses said Sunday.
   The four leaders of Artibonite province were arrested Saturday,
said Samuel Milord, a spokesman for the grassroots organization
Committee for the Defense of Peasant Rights.
   Milord identified those arrested as Dufort Charles, principal
opposition leader in the town of Desdunes, his brother Jackson,
Pierre Simon and Cheniere Santil, all members of the Association
for Development of Desdunes.
   Milord and two other town activists said Jackson Charles and
Santil were beaten by soldiers in the street.
   Government officials were not immediately available for comment.
   Desdunes, 50 miles north of the capital Port-au-Prince, was the
scene of a violent clash Thursday between demonstrators and an
armed gang known as ``The Steamrollers,'' Milord said. One man was
killed and five people were injured.
   The gang included what the three witnesses called ``Macoute
thugs.'' The Tonton Macoutes were the private police force of
former President-for-Life Jean-Claude Duvalier, who was ousted and
fled to France in February 1986.
   He said that also among the 30 men armed with machetes,
revolvers and clubs were Jean-Baptiste Julien, a former development
adviser to ousted Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy; a judge; the town's mayor
and soldiers.
   The three men say most of Desdunes' 14,000 inhabitants fled as a
result of repression by Duvalierists.
   The new president of the military government, Lt. Gen. Prosper
Avril, in power since Namphy was toppled Sept. 17, has vowed to rid
the country of Macoutes and establish democracy in Haiti.
</TEXT>
