<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0246</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Remains Stable, Recovery Of Strength Reported Difficult</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito, bedridden for three weeks, was in
stable condition Monday, but palace authorities said recovery of
his physical strength will be difficult.
   The 87-year-old emperor received 0.42 pints of blood Sunday. He
has received a total of 13.4 pints since his condition worsened.
The total is far more than the normal amount circulating in his
body, according to news reports.
   Hirohito's fever was 99 F Monday morning, unchanged from his
temperature Sunday evening, Imperial Household Agency spokesman
Kenji Maeda said. The emperor's normal temperature is 95.9 F.
   Maeda said there was no further discharge of blood from Sunday
evening through Monday morning.
   In a briefing Sunday evening, Maeda said the ``weakening of his
physical strength... (will make it) difficult for him to regain his
physical strength, and his recovery is not easy as he has been in
bed such a long time.''
   The emperor has been confined to his bed since he vomited a
large amount of blood Sept. 19. The monarch last discharged blood
four days ago.
   The Mainichi Shimbun Monday quoted sources close to palace
doctors as saying the emperor's jaundice ``has progressed'' and
said he is susceptible to hemorrhaging.
   It was the first time such signs have been confirmed, the
nationally circulated newspaper reported.
   News reports say Hirohito has pancreatic cancer, but officials
have neither confirmed nor denied the reports.
</TEXT>
