<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Chemists-Waste     10-09 0235</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemists-Waste,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chemists Urged To Hasten Efforts To End Industrial Discharges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procedures for disposing of industrial waste
are laudable but not enough to protect the environment, the
chairman of the Monsanto Co. said Sunday.
   ``Society's telling us to change,'' said Richard Mahoney. ``We
had better listen. Environmentalists today aren't fringe-element
tree huggers. They're our neighbors, your students, our employees.
You and me.''
   Mahoney spoke to a gathering of chemists and chemical engineers
at the annual meeting of the Council for Chemical Research. He said
current efforts to minimize wastes are laudable but need to be
speeded up, even though the majority of discharges now are made
under strict permits and do not pose a hazard.
   ``Society makes the rules. Reducing wastes is about to become a
rule,'' he said. ``We have a chance now to do that our way _ the
science and technology way _ rather than have some other way
dictated to us later.''
   Mahoney said some of the technology needed to reduce air
emissions and other industrial wastes exists now, but other
technologies will have to be developed. Chemists and engineers will
be at the center of that work, he said.
   ``We're asking you to still keep the costs down, and improve
yields, but at the same time generate little or no waste as a
central part of your effort, not just a welcome byproduct,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
