<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 2322EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0769 10-09 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0769,0893</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS Bunche and Hope obits. AMs separates moved as a0762 on
Gollan, a0683 on Hulton, and on business wires on Emig.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Frank Gollan</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank Gollan, who isolated the polio virus and
invented the first heart-lung machine, and his wife were found dead
at their home Thursday in what their son said appeared to be a
double suicide.
   Gollan, 78, left a note explaining that he and his 81-year-old
wife, Alice, were concerned about their deteriorating health. Andy
Gollan, said he believed his father and stepmother took an overdose
of pills Wednesday night.
   Gollan, who had polio as a child and grew up determined to find
a cure, fled the Nazi occupation of his native Czechoslovakia in
1938 and was qualified as a medical practitioner in Ohio in 1939.
   His isolation of the type MM poliomyelitis virus helped other
scientists in developing a vaccine, and invented a heart-lung
machine for use in open-heart surgery.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Frank Emig</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank W. Emig, director of the AFL-CIO's
department of community services since 1985, died Saturday of
cancer. He was 62.
   Emig for 20 years had headed the labor federation's efforts to
stop the spread of state right-to-work laws that forbid unions from
collecting dues from non-members they represent in collective
bargaining.
   Twenty-one states have such laws now, but only one, Louisiana,
adopted the statute between 1965 and 1985 when Emig headed the
federation's program.
   As director of community services for the AFL-CIO, Emig headed a
network of representatives in 188 cities in 37 states responsible
for coordinating blood drives, food banks and other charities.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Edward Hulton</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sir Edward Hulton, founder of the popular Picture
Post magazine, died Saturday in his sleep. He was 81.
   The Picture Post, founded in 1938, pioneered photojournalism in
Britain, and was bought weekly by millions throughout World War II
and the late 1940s. It folded in June 1957 because of poor
circulation.
   After an early career as a lawyer, Hulton moved into the
publishing business, following in the footsteps of his father who
once owned London's Evening Standard newspaper.
   Hulton owned the entire village of Salperton in Gloucestershire,
western England, where he tried to set up a model farming community.
   Fiercely pro-European, he became editor in chief of the European
Review, a member of the executive committee of the European League
for Economic Cooperation and a member of the British Council of the
European Movement.
   Hulton was married twice, both times to Russian women, and both
marriages were dissolved.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>George Nehrbas</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUAKERTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Y. Nehrbas, who worked his way up
from reporter to managing editor of the Allentown Morning Call,
died Friday. He was 66.
   Nehrbas was born in New York City and graduated from Williams
College, joining the Morning Call staff after returning from World
War II as a Marine lieutenant.
   He worked as reporter, to wire editor, copy editor and assistant
city editor before taking over the managing editor's job, and
retired three years ago.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Thomas Farrell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CANTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brother Thomas S. Farrell, founding
president of Walsh College, died Saturday of a stroke. He was 76.
   He was president of Walsh from November 1960 when the college
opened with 67 students until June 1970, when the school's
enrollment had grown to about 1,000. The liberal arts college
currently has an enrollment of about 1,400.
   From 1970 to 1977, Farrell was assistant director of Catholic
Charities for the Diocese of Youngstown. He then returned to Walsh
College as special assistant to the president. In 1985, he was
named president emeritus, becoming the first person to be granted
emeritus status at Walsh.
   The college's original building, College Hall, was renamed
Farrell Hall in 1977 in honor of Farrell.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Ruth Bunche</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth Harris Bunche, the widow of Nobel Peace
Prize winner and statesman Ralph Bunche, died Saturday of
pancreatic cancer. She was 82.
   A former teacher, Mrs. Bunche served as director of many boards,
including the New York City Youth Board, the Inwood House for Unwed
Mothers, and Japan International Christian University.
   Mrs. Bunche was active in several United Nations-related
organizations, including the Ralph Bunche Institute on the United
Nations and the advisory board of the Metropolitan Chapter of the
U.N. Association of the USA. Her husband, who died in 1971, was a
former U.N. Under Secretary General.
