<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney is leaving little
to chance while he campaigns for a Progressive Conservative Party
victory and for implementing a free trade agreement with the United
States.
   The prime minister's opponents in the heated three-way race for
the Nov. 21 election say a Mulroney victory would mean nothing less
than selling out Canada to its more powerful and richer neighbor.
   The traditional rough-and-tumble of Canadian campaigning was
altered this year by Mulroney's insistence on carefully controlled
public appearances and, at least in the first week of the campaign,
only rare departures from the script.
   Mulroney's two opponents describe their efforts to block the
free trade agreement his government negotiated with the United
States as the fight of the century.

