<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Controllers-Economy     10-09 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Controllers-Economy,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corporate Controllers See Recession Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. corporate controllers increasingly expect
an economic recession next year, with the group overwhelmingly
predicting a recession by 1990, according to a survey by the
National Association of Accountants.
   The controllers, who are responsible for the budgets and
forecasts of their companies, also ranked interest rates as the
factor having the greatest impact on the economy over the next six
months.
   The Montvale, N.J.-based trade group said 47 percent of the
respondents to its fourth quarter economic outlook survey expected
a recession in 1989, compared with 39 percent in the third quarter
outlook survey. Some 57 percent of the respondents expect the
economy to be the same or better 12 months from now.
   For 1990, 62 percent expect a recession, compared with 56
percent in the third quarter outlook.
   The NAA surveyed 3,200 members of its Controllers Counsel during
the fourth week of September, getting a 31 percent response rate.
   Asked to rank the top five factors with the greatest impact on
the economy in the next six months, nearly twice as many executives
chose interest rates as the top factor than any other. Inflation
was ranked second, followed by the federal budget deficit; the
presidential election; and the fluctuation of the dollar.
</TEXT>
