<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Economy-1990s     10-09 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Economy-1990s,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine: Recession Will Usher In Moderate Growth, Inflation In
1990s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The economy of the 1990s may get off to a shaky
start, but in the longer-term it could feature steady growth,
higher taxes, high employment and low interest rates, according to
a forecast by Money magazine.
   The magazine, in a special Fall 1988 edition, also predicted
that while the 1990a economy would not necessarily boom, it would
provide a good background for another bull market in stocks and
bonds.
   Money said its forecast was based on observations by a panel of
six economic and social experts, plus interviews with about 300
economists, demographers, investment analysts, futurists and others
who monitor trends and forecast change.
   The magazine indicated its experts generally expected no
economic recession during this election year. It also predicted
that when a recession did occur it should be mild by historical
standards, tempered by the continued steady demand for services,
which now account for 67 percent of the gross national product and
90 percent of new jobs.
   Furthermore, the increasingly deregulated global economy tends
to be more self-regulating, the magazine stated, with interest
rates rising in overheated economies to help choke off inflation
and economic booms, thus lessening the severity of booms and busts.
   Among other predictions for the 1990s:
   _Following recession, the economy will enjoy moderate inflation
and steady, moderate growth;
   _Unemployment could fall as low as 4 percent due to the expected
``baby bust'' that will see workforce growth slow sharply;
   _The dollar will decline slightly but will bottom out, helping
further trim the U.S. trade deficit;
   _The next president _ whoever it is _ will raise taxes within
two years;
   _Long-term interest rates will peak at 10.5 percent to 11
percent and later fall to as low as 5 percent, due to lower credit
demand during the recession;
   _The Dow Jones industrial average _ now at about 2,150 _ will
hit 3,000 early in the next decade as falling interest rates on
bonds encourage investors to switch to stocks;
   _Investors increasingly will invest for the long-term, amid
sagging confidence in Social Security and increasing awareness of
rising future costs, such as college.
   Pessimists among the magazine's experts warned the 1990s
scenario could be bleak, with the recession possibly deepening into
a depression. A worst-case scenario could be set up by:
   _Faulty U.S. government policy, such as a tax increase that
might stifle economic growth by forcing debt-burdened consumers to
cut their spending, reducing a key GNP component;
   _A surge in bank failures that also might prompt consumers to
cut spending drastically;
   _Protectionism combining with a recently-stronger dollar to
widen the nation's trade deficit;
   _A crash of the high-flying Japanese stock market, which could
cause huge Japanese investment firms to dump U.S. stocks and bonds,
forcing interest rates here to skyrocket.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
