<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Libya-OPEC     10-09 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Libya-OPEC,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libya Calls For Extraordinary OPEC Meeting On Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya on Sunday called for an extraordinary meeting
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, to restore
falling oil prices.
   According to the official Libyan news agency JANA, monitored
here, Libya called for a urgent conference of the OPEC Ministerial
Council as soon as possible.
   It said the council should ``take the necessary measures to stop
the fall in prices, restore stability to the oil market and to take
prices up to levels which are fair to both consumer and producer.''
   Oil prices tumbled last week to their lowest levels since 1986,
and now are just under $13 a barrel in the U.S. futures market.
   Some analysts blamed the sharp decline on indications that more
Saudi Arabian crude will be flowing into the market. The Saudis
have indicated they may hike production unless other members of the
13-nation OPEC adhere to production quotas aimed at supporting a
benchmark price of $18 a barrel.
   JANA said Libya's decision to call for the extraordinary meeting
was made ``after consultation with some OPEC member countries.''
</TEXT>
