<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 2017EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-09 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0545</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's unemployment rate in September
fell back to July's level of 5.4 percent, but with the loss of
37,000 factory jobs in the meantime, the government said.
   Employers added 255,000 new jobs to their payrolls last month,
sending the number of unemployed workers down by a like figure to
6,596,000, the Labor Department reported Friday.
   The unemployment total was the lowest it has been since June,
when the jobless rate hit a 14-year-low of 5.3 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's business leaders, enjoying
high profits from the strongest economic growth in four years, said
they expect a slowdown in 1989.
   Executives ranging from Citicorp Chairman John S. Reed to
General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger B. Smith said Friday that their
industries are generating very strong earnings.
   Nevertheless, the chief executives said they would prefer less
robust growth and a ``soft landing'' next year to the alternative:
higher inflation, rising interest rates and finally a recession, or
a ``hard landing.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans took out consumer credit at an
annual rate of 10.1 percent in August, up substantially from the
July borrowing pace, the government reported.
   The Federal Reserve said Friday that consumers took out $5.44
billion more in credit than they paid off in August, as auto loans
and credit card debt grew more rapidly.
   Consumer debt had risen $3.62 billion in July, a 6.7 percent
annual rate, as the pace of borrowing slowed momentarily following
several months of rapid gains.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kroger Co. rejected two buyout proposals by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. and reaffirmed its intent to go ahead
with a $4.6 billion corporate restructuring plan.
   The supermarket giant said Friday that its board of directors
unanimously rejected both of the latest unsolicited proposals made
by Kohlberg Kravis in an Oct. 4 letter to Kroger.
   The restructuring plan prompted the firing of 300 headquarters
employees announced earlier in the week.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Irving Bank Corp.'s board of directors approved
a management-backed $1.48 billion merger with hostile suitor Bank
of New York Co., ending one of the nation's longest and most bitter
takeover battles.
   The merger approved Friday will nearly double Bank of New York's
size, vaulting it close to the top 10 of the nation's largest
banking companies. The two had a combined $47.8 billion in assets
as of June 30.
   The board vote came two days after Irving Chairman Joseph A.
Rice announced he would abandon his year-long resistance to the
proposed acquisition and drop all pending lawsuits and
anti-takeover defenses aimed at stopping Bank of New York.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MCorp, Texas' second-largest bank-holding company
and the last of the state's major banks to avoid seeking outside
help, said it is seeking a federal bailout in its proposed
recapitalization.
   The bank said Friday it could not predict when or how much aid
it would request.
   The bank's third-quarter results, due out by Tuesday, are
expected to show a bigger jump in non-performing assets than the
$158 million increase posted in the second quarter.
</TEXT>
