<FILEID>AP-NR-10-09-88 2156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MGM-UAChairman     10-09 0430</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-MGM-UA Chairman,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Silbert Resigning as CEO-Chairman, Barbakow Will Take Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen D. Silbert is resigning as
board chairman and chief executive officer of MGM-UA Communications
Co., and Merrill Lynch executive Jeffrey C. Barbakow will take over
as president.
   The studio announced Sunday that Silbert was resigning to take a
position with Tracinda Corp., the company's principal shareholder,
becoming the latest to join an exodus of top executives from MGM-UA.
   ``I assumed the chairman's postion at MGM-UA as an interim step
until a permanent team could be named,'' Silbert explained.
   Barbakow, managing director in charge of the Pacific Southwest
Region of the Investment Banking Division of Merrill Lynch Capital
Markets, has expertise on mergers and and acquisitions, MGM-UA said
in a news release.
   ``We will implement the plans recently announced by the
company,'' Barbakow said in the statement. ``Moreover, we expect to
supplement the company's financial resources in order to resume a
full development and production slate and to provide capital for
the company's other operations.''
   The company said only that Barbakow would be named ``later this
week.''
   MGM-UA also announced that Kenin M. Spivak, also an
entertainment industry specialist at Merrill Lynch Capital Markets,
will be named executive vice president, and Trevor Fetter, also of
Merrill Lynch, will be net senior vice president.
   Silbert will remain with the company until Jan. 15 to assist
Barbakow in the transition, the company said. He also will remain a
member of the executive committee and the board of directors of
MGM-UA.
   A corporate restructuring of MGM-UA includes a $200 million plan
that calls for present stockholders to be given the right to buy
additional new shares in MGM-UA, maker of Academy Award-winning
``Moonstruck,'' the company said last month.
   The restructuring, disclosed in a cryptic announcement by
MGM-UA, appears to depend on a substantial injection of cash from
Kirk Kerkorian, the Los Angeles investor who owns 79 percent of the
show-business conglomerate.
   Kerkorian's Tracinda Corp. intends to buy any of the new shares
that aren't taken by other stockholders, the company said.
   Recent executive departures at MGM-UA include ex-UA chairman and
chief executive Anthony Thomopoulos, MGM-UA chairman and chief
executive Lee Rich and MGM production unit chief Alan Ladd Jr.
   ``I believe that by creating a stable environment with ample
funds available for production, MGM-UA will be able to strengthen
its position as a major supplier of entertainment programming,''
Barbakow said. ``We intend to draw upon our strong business
relationships in the community and our comprehensive experience in
arranging financings to maximize the value of the company.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
